face in the United States today

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:05.380
is that our political system
is over here, very much

00:02:05.380 --> 00:02:07.880
bounded by moneyed interests.

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:10.160
But the great bulk of the
population isn't with that.

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:10.910
They're over here.

00:02:10.910 --> 00:02:12.830
They want real solutions
to real problems

00:02:12.830 --> 00:02:13.885
that our country faces.

00:02:13.885 --> 00:02:16.010
And they know that our
government needs to provide.

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:19.120
And this tension is growing
greater and greater by the day.

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:20.860
And it's that
tension that's going

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:25.610
to create the birth, we
think, or the rejuvenation

00:02:25.610 --> 00:02:28.990
of a movement to really
re-democratize this country

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:31.970
or democratize it much
more than it is at present.

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:34.950
When we talk about
dollarocracy, what we refer to

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:36.260
is fairly self-evident.

00:02:36.260 --> 00:02:39.520
Democracy means the rule of
the people, the rule of money.

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:42.470
Going from the
Greeks, dollarocracy

00:02:42.470 --> 00:02:45.280
means the rule of money,
not the rule of people.

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:47.734
$1, one vote rather than
one person, one vote.

00:02:47.734 --> 00:02:50.150
Those with a great deal of
money have tremendous influence

00:02:50.150 --> 00:02:51.510
over politics.

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:54.220
Those with no money
have no influence

00:02:54.220 --> 00:02:56.590
over politics whatsoever.

00:02:56.590 --> 00:02:59.560
Two recent studies published
by Princeton University Press

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:02.040
really encapsulated
this problem,

00:03:02.040 --> 00:03:04.820
one by Marty Gilens, another
by a team of scholars.

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:08.075
They reached independently
the exact same conclusion,

00:03:08.075 --> 00:03:10.450
which is if you look at the
Congress of the United States

00:03:10.450 --> 00:03:13.950
today, none of the
decisions that are made

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:15.890
reflect the interests
of the great majority

00:03:15.890 --> 00:03:18.560
of the voters of this country,
the values of their voters.

00:03:18.560 --> 00:03:21.390
Representatives routinely ignore
what their own constituents

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:23.370
want when they deal
with their decisions.

00:03:23.370 --> 00:03:25.740
The decisions are
made almost entirely

00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:29.030
on behalf of the most
wealthy and powerful,

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:32.380
self-interested
parties to the policy

00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:35.420
or the law or the budget item.

00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:38.190
A month ago, we were
in Washington, DC.

00:03:38.190 --> 00:03:40.450
And we had a book launch party.

00:03:40.450 --> 00:03:43.580
And the person who wrote
the foreword to our book

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:46.970
graciously introduced us,
US Senator Bernie Sanders.

00:03:46.970 --> 00:03:49.090
Bernie has been in the US
Senate now seven years.

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:50.670
Before that, he
served eight terms

00:03:50.670 --> 00:03:52.790
in the US House of
Representatives.

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:55.920
And he said, unequivocally,
unconditionally,

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:57.450
that it is impossible
for anything

00:03:57.450 --> 00:03:59.330
to pass the US Congress
if it is opposed

00:03:59.330 --> 00:04:03.180
by either corporate America
or Wall Street-- impossible.

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:07.150
They basically have veto
power over all legislation.

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:09.420
And that, in a nutshell,
is dollarocracy.

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:11.650
That's not democracy.

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:14.330
Just this last summer, Jimmy
Carter, the former president,

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:17.540
was meeting with a number
of dignitaries from Germany,

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:19.850
talking about American
and global politics.

00:04:19.850 --> 00:04:22.100
It was supposed to be an
off-the-record meeting.

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:23.670
Thanks to the
presence of an iPhone,

00:04:23.670 --> 00:04:25.960
it became an
on-the-record meeting.

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:27.860
And Carter said,
the United States

00:04:27.860 --> 00:04:30.920
is "no longer a
functional democracy."

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:32.420
No longer a
functional democracy.

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:34.190
We are off the Democratic grid.

00:04:34.190 --> 00:04:36.400
We no longer have
the rule of law.

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:39.360
We no longer have the
accountability one associates

00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:43.170
at the base level with a
self-governing or democratic

00:04:43.170 --> 00:04:44.241
society.

00:04:44.241 --> 00:04:45.740
And then to top it
off, in the book,

00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:48.425
we go through a lot of the
polling data and survey

00:04:48.425 --> 00:04:50.800
data that shows that most
Americans are familiar with it.

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:52.650
This is not something
that shocks Americans.

00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:53.270
They get it.

00:04:53.270 --> 00:04:55.700
They understand
the powerlessness

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:58.110
they have politically
that's frustrating to them.

00:04:58.110 --> 00:05:01.290
One survey that's most
striking was that almost half

00:05:01.290 --> 00:05:04.640
of Americans think we would have
a better Congress if we simply

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:07.550
drew names out of a hat rather
than went through the election

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:08.050
process.

00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:09.260
That's a laugh line.

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:11.213
But then people think
about it and say,

00:05:11.213 --> 00:05:13.360
you know, maybe that's
not such a bad idea.

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:15.970
For those of you who know your
history of democratic theory,

00:05:15.970 --> 00:05:18.430
that's how the ancient Greeks
made most their decisions.

00:05:18.430 --> 00:05:21.720
It came through the jury
system, not through elections.

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:24.680
So at any rate, dollarocracy
is the term we have for this.

00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:26.150
And it has immense consequences.

00:05:26.150 --> 00:05:28.483
The most obvious ones, the
ones we're all familiar with,

00:05:28.483 --> 00:05:29.440
is corruption.

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:32.720
That the decisions that are
made in budgets and policies

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:36.450
and laws are dominated by
self-interested, large,

00:05:36.450 --> 00:05:38.440
profitable commercial interests.

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:40.380
But it also has a lot
of other consequences.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:41.796
And they are the
consequences that

00:05:41.796 --> 00:05:44.257
really shape the
life of this country

00:05:44.257 --> 00:05:45.840
going forward until
they're addressed,

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:49.080
until something is done
about dollarocracy.

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:51.760
We have seen a massive increase
of an inequality in the United

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.100
States in the last 35 years.

00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:56.530
And this is what you would
expect in a dollarocracy.

00:05:56.530 --> 00:05:59.380
Those at the top rig the
system so the funds go to them.

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:00.850
The benefits go to them.

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:03.300
And the resources don't
flow towards the bottom.

00:06:03.300 --> 00:06:06.570
We've seen an enormous increase
in poverty in the last 35 years

00:06:06.570 --> 00:06:08.030
in the United States.

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:09.920
Virtually all the
gains we made, which

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:13.710
were enormous from the 1920s
to the 1960s to reduce poverty,

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:14.430
have been lost.

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:17.435
We're back at poverty rates and
low income rates in the United

00:06:17.435 --> 00:06:20.510
States today equivalent to
where we were 80 years ago.

00:06:20.510 --> 00:06:23.920
We've lost almost all our
gains in the past generation.

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:26.120
Economic stagnation.

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:29.430
The certified range of
debate over economic policy

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:31.690
by the dollarcrats
in Washington, DC,

00:06:31.690 --> 00:06:34.430
is entirely comfortable with
high rates of unemployment

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:36.780
and lower real wages
for most workers.

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:39.430
That's just not even debated
by either party, by anyone,

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:40.160
in Washington.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:43.110
It's just a narrow
range of debate.

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:44.389
That's not much of a future.

00:06:44.389 --> 00:06:46.680
Basically, what we have now,
based on current policies,

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:48.190
is what we're
getting going forward

00:06:48.190 --> 00:06:50.440
for the great bulk
of American people.

00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:53.167
And then there's another point
here that's too often lost.

00:06:53.167 --> 00:06:55.500
One of the great things about
America, one of the things

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:57.000
I think all Americans
treasure most,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.160
is our civil liberties-- freedom
of speech, freedom of religion,

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:03.720
freedom of the press, right
to assemble peacefully.

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:07.270
Well, when you lose democracy,
when it becomes a dollarocracy,

00:07:07.270 --> 00:07:09.780
your liberties, those
rights we cherish the most,

00:07:09.780 --> 00:07:11.890
are on softer ground.

00:07:11.890 --> 00:07:13.960
You still have the right
to tattoo something

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:16.659
on your forehead or to have
a haircut of your choosing.

00:07:16.659 --> 00:07:18.200
But when you start
challenging people

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:20.780
in power, what rights really
are all about, the ability

00:07:20.780 --> 00:07:24.310
to stand up to those in power,
you're on softer ground.

00:07:24.310 --> 00:07:27.367
And we've seen, for example,
just this last week, a week

00:07:27.367 --> 00:07:29.450
and a half ago, for the
first time in its history,

00:07:29.450 --> 00:07:31.754
the Committee to Protect
Journalists, an organization

00:07:31.754 --> 00:07:34.170
which defends freedom of the
press and journalists' rights

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:37.250
worldwide against autocratic
governments for the first time

00:07:37.250 --> 00:07:39.440
issued a report on
harassment of journalists

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:42.170
by the US government--
first time in its history.

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:45.160
And I'd submit that's what
you get in dollarocracy.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:47.160
Under dollarocracy,
those rights,

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:50.000
those freedoms that we once
took for granted to the extent

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.530
they mix with people in power,
suddenly are less secure.

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:57.580
Well, the solution, in our
view, to dollarocracy is clear.

00:07:57.580 --> 00:07:58.920
It's democracy.

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:00.770
And in this book,
what we argue is

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:03.940
that the election system, which
is the main way citizens have

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:08.090
a way to exercise democracy,
has been greatly corrupted.

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:09.790
And that's really
where the problem is.

00:08:09.790 --> 00:08:11.740
And our book looks at
how it's been corrupted.

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:14.120
So the ability of the
vote and the voter

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:15.880
has been reduced tremendously.

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:19.790
And money has come to
rule it a great deal.

00:08:19.790 --> 00:08:21.370
Now, our book is
fairly depressing.

00:08:21.370 --> 00:08:22.780
You can always get
the vibe right now

00:08:22.780 --> 00:08:25.071
where I'm going with it,
where we're going in the book.

00:08:25.071 --> 00:08:28.000
But American history is
not a constant series

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.900
of depressing outcomes,
quite the contrary.

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:34.480
Between 1900 and 1970,
democratic forces,

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:35.980
popular forces in
the United States,

00:08:35.980 --> 00:08:39.049
won a number of enormous
victories, huge victories.

00:08:39.049 --> 00:08:40.640
We won the right to
have trade unions.

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:43.169
We won social security.

00:08:43.169 --> 00:08:44.169
We won Medicare.

00:08:44.169 --> 00:08:48.140
We established public education
for working class people

00:08:48.140 --> 00:08:50.420
vastly superior to almost
anywhere in the world.

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:53.340
We extended higher education
to a higher percentage

00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:55.890
of the population than
anywhere else in the world.

00:08:55.890 --> 00:08:57.630
We reduced poverty dramatically.

00:08:57.630 --> 00:09:00.300
And by the 1960s, we had
less economic inequality

00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:02.990
than we'd ever had since
the Industrial Revolution.

00:09:02.990 --> 00:09:05.450
We were really,
in many respects,

00:09:05.450 --> 00:09:06.900
moving forward rapidly.

00:09:06.900 --> 00:09:08.010
Now, it was up and down.

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:08.760
There were fights.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:09.593
There were contests.

00:09:09.593 --> 00:09:11.300
It wasn't all wins.

00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:13.250
But it wasn't all
defeats either.

00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:16.280
By the end of the 1960s,
and I was a teenager then,

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:19.440
they did a survey in 1970 of
all the teenagers in the world.

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:21.610
And they found out
that American teenagers

00:09:21.610 --> 00:09:24.040
were among the three most
optimistic groups of teenagers

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:24.581
in the world.

00:09:24.581 --> 00:09:27.150
The other two were
Israeli and Chilean.

00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:29.900
Chile fell off the
list a few years later.

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:31.319
And America fell
off the list too.

00:09:31.319 --> 00:09:32.860
We're way down the
list now when they

00:09:32.860 --> 00:09:35.890
do those surveys
in 40, 50, 60, 70.

00:09:35.890 --> 00:09:37.600
We're nowhere near the top.

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:38.750
And I was a teenager then.

00:09:38.750 --> 00:09:40.208
And I remember the
optimism we had.

00:09:40.208 --> 00:09:43.580
We thought this country had the
capacity to solve its problems.

00:09:43.580 --> 00:09:45.127
We made all this progress.

00:09:45.127 --> 00:09:47.210
And we were within eyesight
of a much better world

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:50.530
with even less inequality, less
poverty, more opportunity, more

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:54.060
justice, less
militarism, and less war.

00:09:54.060 --> 00:09:57.240
But not everyone was
optimistic in the early 1970s.

00:09:57.240 --> 00:09:59.509
In particular,
the leading lights

00:09:59.509 --> 00:10:01.800
in the business community
were deeply concerned by what

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:04.420
they saw going on in
America at that time.

00:10:04.420 --> 00:10:06.090
They were concerned
that America was not

00:10:06.090 --> 00:10:08.298
sufficiently reverential
towards traditional business

00:10:08.298 --> 00:10:10.020
domination of politics.

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:12.630
They were deeply concerned that
the most honored and respected

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:16.120
person in American life in 1970
across the political spectrum

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:17.600
was Ralph Nader.

00:10:17.600 --> 00:10:22.100
Ralph Nader, who's vision
was that public service was

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:26.170
the highest calling a person
could do to serve others

00:10:26.170 --> 00:10:27.680
and that people
could work together

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:30.160
and democratically have the
government solve problems

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:31.520
effectively on behalf
of all the people.

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:32.895
The government
did not have to be

00:10:32.895 --> 00:10:35.510
a source of
corruption or tyranny.

00:10:35.510 --> 00:10:36.660
That was Nader's message.

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:38.243
And this scared the
business community

00:10:38.243 --> 00:10:41.410
to death, which saw its
stature in the country

00:10:41.410 --> 00:10:45.340
probably at its lowest ebb in
generations by the early 1970s,

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:48.117
especially, interesting
enough, among middle class

00:10:48.117 --> 00:10:49.450
and upper middle class students.

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:50.590
College students,
who traditionally

00:10:50.590 --> 00:10:52.430
were the backbone
of business society,

00:10:52.430 --> 00:10:55.220
suddenly had a marked
increase in concern

00:10:55.220 --> 00:10:58.040
that large corporations
weren't the best

00:10:58.040 --> 00:11:01.380
way to structure an
economy for a free society.

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:03.930
In the early 1970s, the
US Chamber of Commerce

00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:06.310
commissioned a confidential
memo to be distributed

00:11:06.310 --> 00:11:10.517
among five or six dozen
leading CEOs and investors

00:11:10.517 --> 00:11:12.600
to deal with what they
termed the political crisis

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:13.550
of our time.

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:15.400
And they termed it the
crisis of democracy.

00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:17.260
And the crisis of
democracy to them

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:19.400
was that there was
too much democracy.

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:21.850
The crisis of democracy
was that women,

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:24.017
African Americans, young
people, young workers, who

00:11:24.017 --> 00:11:26.100
traditionally had been
apathetic and not concerned

00:11:26.100 --> 00:11:28.370
with politics, had gotten
too engaged in politics,

00:11:28.370 --> 00:11:30.660
were making demands on the
system the system really

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:31.700
couldn't accommodate.

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:34.360
We had to get them back on the
couches, back in apathetic,

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:36.759
back and unconcerned
with politics.

00:11:36.759 --> 00:11:38.550
And the US Chamber of
Commerce commissioned

00:11:38.550 --> 00:11:40.258
the leading corporate
attorney in America

00:11:40.258 --> 00:11:41.810
at that time to write a memo.

00:11:41.810 --> 00:11:44.090
And this attorney's
name was Lewis Powell,

00:11:44.090 --> 00:11:46.650
who made a vast fortune
representing firms, especially

00:11:46.650 --> 00:11:48.280
in the US tobacco industry.

00:11:48.280 --> 00:11:52.477
And the Powell memo, you can
Google it after the talk.

00:11:52.477 --> 00:11:53.060
It's up there.

00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:53.930
It's six pages long.

00:11:53.930 --> 00:11:54.955
It was done in 1971.

00:11:54.955 --> 00:11:57.080
It was a blueprint, basically,
for how corporations

00:11:57.080 --> 00:11:58.680
can take over the
government of the country

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:00.304
with the goal of
making it very simple.

00:12:00.304 --> 00:12:02.870
No matter who wins
the election, we win.

00:12:02.870 --> 00:12:04.740
Business domination
of society is never

00:12:04.740 --> 00:12:06.270
in question
whichever party wins.

00:12:06.270 --> 00:12:07.800
That was the mission of it.

00:12:07.800 --> 00:12:09.530
And what Powell argued
was that business

00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:11.870
needed to devote immense
resources to lobbying

00:12:11.870 --> 00:12:13.010
and politics.

00:12:13.010 --> 00:12:15.100
And in the two decades
following the memo,

00:12:15.100 --> 00:12:17.940
there's was a tenfold increase,
10 times increase in lobbying

00:12:17.940 --> 00:12:20.530
and political spending
by corporations.

00:12:20.530 --> 00:12:23.630
10 times increase in the number
of lobbyists in Washington, DC.

00:12:23.630 --> 00:12:26.650
The term K Street, which
didn't exist before 1971,

00:12:26.650 --> 00:12:29.230
became a term like Wall
Street or Madison Avenue

00:12:29.230 --> 00:12:31.430
to signify an enormous industry.

00:12:31.430 --> 00:12:33.890
Washington, DC, which had
been a sleepy backwater

00:12:33.890 --> 00:12:35.720
town without much
wealth, compared

00:12:35.720 --> 00:12:38.000
to the Clevelands, or
the Bay Areas, or the New

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.620
Yorks, or the Philadelphias
of the world, suddenly,

00:12:40.620 --> 00:12:43.844
after the influx of corporate
money and the lobbying,

00:12:43.844 --> 00:12:45.260
became a very
different community.

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:47.980
Today, four or five of the 10
richest counties in the United

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:51.040
States are the suburbs
ringing Washington, DC.

00:12:51.040 --> 00:12:53.390
And those aren't government
bureaucrats living there.

00:12:53.390 --> 00:12:54.830
They're the people of K Street.

00:12:54.830 --> 00:12:56.871
They're the corporate
people living there and all

00:12:56.871 --> 00:12:58.610
their ancillary people.

00:12:58.610 --> 00:12:59.720
So they've succeeded.

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:02.900
Now, one thing that Powell
was insistent on in his memo

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:04.870
was they needed to
build groups that

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:07.770
would buttress the ideological
and political power

00:13:07.770 --> 00:13:10.980
of corporations-- Heritage
Foundation, CATO, American

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:13.340
Enterprise Institute came
immediately following this.

00:13:13.340 --> 00:13:15.631
ALEC, a group that you've
been learning more about here

00:13:15.631 --> 00:13:19.010
at Google apparently, came
immediately after this.

00:13:19.010 --> 00:13:21.770
And then, most
importantly, we've

00:13:21.770 --> 00:13:23.850
got to do something
about the Supreme Court.

00:13:23.850 --> 00:13:26.150
Even when we have
Republican presidents who

00:13:26.150 --> 00:13:28.240
are pro-business, like
Eisenhower and Nixon,

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:31.160
they're appointing these guys
like Earl Warren and Harry

00:13:31.160 --> 00:13:31.795
Blackmun.

00:13:31.795 --> 00:13:33.295
And they get a
lifetime appointment.

00:13:33.295 --> 00:13:35.378
And they get carried away
with the First Amendment

00:13:35.378 --> 00:13:37.994
and the idea of
expanding democracy.

00:13:37.994 --> 00:13:40.160
We've got to get guys in
the court, when we put them

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:41.743
on the court, we
know they will always

00:13:41.743 --> 00:13:43.770
understand business
first, business always.

00:13:43.770 --> 00:13:45.140
Business has to dominate.

00:13:45.140 --> 00:13:47.390
So they set up something
called The Federalist Society

00:13:47.390 --> 00:13:49.259
to be a training ground
for their attorneys,

00:13:49.259 --> 00:13:51.550
so they could count on them
when they got in the court.

00:13:51.550 --> 00:13:54.030
And as fate would have it,
two months after this Powell

00:13:54.030 --> 00:13:56.530
memo was distributed
confidentially and gendered

00:13:56.530 --> 00:13:58.840
a great deal of discussion
internally in the business

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:02.240
community, there's an opening
on the US Supreme Court.

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:05.390
And who should President
Nixon decide to appoint?

00:14:05.390 --> 00:14:06.670
Lewis Powell.

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:08.600
He became the next judge
in the Supreme Court.

00:14:08.600 --> 00:14:10.610
So he had a chance to
swing right into action

00:14:10.610 --> 00:14:14.060
and implement his ideas as a
member of the US Supreme Court.

00:14:14.060 --> 00:14:15.995
And Powell's signature
issue from the moment

00:14:15.995 --> 00:14:17.370
he came to the
court was the idea

00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:19.710
there should be unlimited
spending by corporations

00:14:19.710 --> 00:14:21.740
and wealthy people on politics.

00:14:21.740 --> 00:14:22.980
That was his immediate issue.

00:14:22.980 --> 00:14:24.637
He was obsessed with that.

00:14:24.637 --> 00:14:26.970
He was never able to win that
fight on the Supreme Court

00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:28.845
while he was on it,
because the Chief Justice

00:14:28.845 --> 00:14:30.510
at the time, William
Rehnquist, was

00:14:30.510 --> 00:14:31.520
an old-fashioned conservative.

00:14:31.520 --> 00:14:33.240
He didn't believe
corporations were people.

00:14:33.240 --> 00:14:34.990
He didn't believe the
Supreme Court should

00:14:34.990 --> 00:14:38.640
mess with the structure of
elections to play favorites.

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:40.940
He opposed the efforts
to have unleashed money.

00:14:40.940 --> 00:14:42.740
But by the time John
Roberts replaced

00:14:42.740 --> 00:14:45.360
Rehnquist in 2010,
all that changed.

00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:48.330
John Roberts was a
Federalist Society superstar.

00:14:48.330 --> 00:14:50.600
He was committed to
unlimited spending

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:53.390
by business and billionaires
and trade unions.

00:14:53.390 --> 00:14:54.859
And for those of
the younger people

00:14:54.859 --> 00:14:57.150
here, ask some of the old
people what trade unions are.

00:14:57.150 --> 00:15:00.690
They're these things we used to
have back in the '60s and '70s

00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:04.800
that gave workers some higher
income than they have today.

00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:07.930
And the Citizens United
decision came on in 2010.

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:10.080
And that's really what
drove this book, because

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:14.180
with Citizens United, what we
saw was businesses, unions,

00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:16.185
and billionaires can
spend unlimited amounts

00:15:16.185 --> 00:15:18.310
on political campaigns, as
long as the money didn't

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:20.460
go officially to
the campaign itself.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:22.737
It went to a third-party
group that was not

00:15:22.737 --> 00:15:24.320
associated with the
campaign but could

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:27.800
be linked to it informally,
as we learned in 2012.

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:31.015
And as a result, we saw in
the last election, 2012,

00:15:31.015 --> 00:15:34.250
in the United States,
we spent $10.3 billion

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:36.080
on all our elections,
double what

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:38.300
was spent in 2008
and all the elections

00:15:38.300 --> 00:15:41.800
in America, 10 times what
was spent 20 years ago,

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:43.540
even factoring inflation.

00:15:43.540 --> 00:15:46.540
We're way huge
increase in spending.

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:49.612
Now, the Supreme Court argued
this huge increase in spending

00:15:49.612 --> 00:15:51.570
would be a good thing,
because there would just

00:15:51.570 --> 00:15:52.660
be more civic virtue.

00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:55.720
More money is more speech,
more involvement by people.

00:15:55.720 --> 00:15:58.126
But there's a fundamental
problem with that argument.

00:15:58.126 --> 00:15:59.750
There's a big difference
between anyone

00:15:59.750 --> 00:16:01.880
in this room giving
$50, $100, $200, even

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:05.320
$1,000 to a candidate
and someone giving

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:07.450
100 times or 1,000 times that.

00:16:07.450 --> 00:16:09.550
It goes from being
a civic contribution

00:16:09.550 --> 00:16:12.600
to being an investment with an
expected outcome commercially.

00:16:12.600 --> 00:16:14.960
All the evidence has
always pointed that way.

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:17.330
All the evidence continues
to point that way.

00:16:17.330 --> 00:16:20.476
Now, it's difficult to fully
get the evidence on that

00:16:20.476 --> 00:16:22.350
in the short term,
because most of the people

00:16:22.350 --> 00:16:23.570
are dropping lots of money.

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:25.110
And much of this money
is now anonymous.

00:16:25.110 --> 00:16:26.568
As we chronicled
in the book, there

00:16:26.568 --> 00:16:27.830
are no records that are kept.

00:16:27.830 --> 00:16:28.996
Don't want to be publicized.

00:16:28.996 --> 00:16:32.910
If you drop $50 or $100
million on a referendum case

00:16:32.910 --> 00:16:34.624
on labeling of
foods in California,

00:16:34.624 --> 00:16:36.040
for example, you
don't really want

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:37.730
to necessarily
advertise who you are.

00:16:37.730 --> 00:16:40.063
You want to keep it on the
down low as much as possible.

00:16:40.063 --> 00:16:41.200
You just want to win.

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:43.160
But fortunately for us
in doing our research,

00:16:43.160 --> 00:16:45.890
there was one major donor
who gave $200 million

00:16:45.890 --> 00:16:48.490
in the last election cycle
who enjoyed the publicity

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:49.760
and reveled in it.

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:51.170
He's from Las Vegas, Nevada.

00:16:51.170 --> 00:16:52.780
His name is Shelly Adelson.

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:54.100
You might have heard of him.

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:55.785
Shelly dropped $200
million, as I said.

00:16:55.785 --> 00:16:58.160
And after the election, everyone
said, well, poor Shelly.

00:16:58.160 --> 00:16:59.490
He lost $200 million.

00:16:59.490 --> 00:17:00.420
He had a rough year.

00:17:00.420 --> 00:17:02.090
All his candidates lost.

00:17:02.090 --> 00:17:03.630
Well, not all of them.

00:17:03.630 --> 00:17:05.778
In Michigan, there
was a referendum

00:17:05.778 --> 00:17:08.319
on the ballot to make the right
to have collective bargaining

00:17:08.319 --> 00:17:10.050
part of the Michigan
constitution

00:17:10.050 --> 00:17:12.710
so the government couldn't take
away that right from workers.

00:17:12.710 --> 00:17:13.890
It looked like it
was going to win.

00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:15.089
Michigan, after
all, is the backbone

00:17:15.089 --> 00:17:17.069
of the labor movement
in the United States.

00:17:17.069 --> 00:17:19.050
In the last few weeks,
Shelly took an interest

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:22.250
in that state in that race and
dropped a few million dollars

00:17:22.250 --> 00:17:24.099
quickly to run
negative ads against it

00:17:24.099 --> 00:17:26.254
and was able to defeat
it at the last second.

00:17:26.254 --> 00:17:27.170
So he won some things.

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:29.242
He didn't lose everything.

00:17:29.242 --> 00:17:31.200
Shelly Adelson had a very
interesting interview

00:17:31.200 --> 00:17:34.422
after the 2012 election.

00:17:34.422 --> 00:17:36.255
He went to Washington
so all the Republicans

00:17:36.255 --> 00:17:37.970
could kiss his ring.

00:17:37.970 --> 00:17:39.720
And "The Washington
Post" interviewed him.

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:41.830
And the reporter said, what are
your politics, Shelly Adelson?

00:17:41.830 --> 00:17:42.750
What motivates you?

00:17:42.750 --> 00:17:45.150
He said, well, these
are my political values.

00:17:45.150 --> 00:17:47.720
I believe in
socialized medicine.

00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:50.320
I believe in stem cell research.

00:17:50.320 --> 00:17:51.946
I'm concerned about
the climate crisis.

00:17:51.946 --> 00:17:54.111
I think we probably have
to do something about that.

00:17:54.111 --> 00:17:55.100
I believe in science.

00:17:55.100 --> 00:17:57.270
I believe in a woman's
right to choose.

00:17:57.270 --> 00:17:59.090
I believe in gay rights
and gay marriage.

00:17:59.090 --> 00:18:01.634
The reporter is dumbfounded.

00:18:01.634 --> 00:18:04.050
Are you the same Shelly Adelson
who just gave $200 million

00:18:04.050 --> 00:18:06.260
to Rick Santorum and
all these lunatics?

00:18:06.260 --> 00:18:08.720
And I'm paraphrasing here.

00:18:08.720 --> 00:18:09.550
And he said, yeah.

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:12.130
He said, I don't give money
to politics for those reasons.

00:18:12.130 --> 00:18:15.410
When I give money to politics,
I've got three basic concerns.

00:18:15.410 --> 00:18:17.980
Number one, I hate labor unions.

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:19.040
I have a nonunion shop.

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:19.810
I'm a billionaire.

00:18:19.810 --> 00:18:21.370
I don't want to have
the unions in my shop.

00:18:21.370 --> 00:18:22.500
So I'm for politicians
who are going

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:24.420
to make sure we don't have
to worry about labor unions.

00:18:24.420 --> 00:18:26.140
Number two, I'm
worth $30 billion.

00:18:26.140 --> 00:18:27.590
I don't like paying taxes.

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:29.140
That's for the little people.

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:30.970
I want politicians
to keep my taxes low.

00:18:30.970 --> 00:18:33.870
And for what I spend, I get
a 1% drop in my tax rate.

00:18:33.870 --> 00:18:36.620
It more than pays for whatever
I give any politician.

00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:38.530
And number three, I
run gambling casinos.

00:18:38.530 --> 00:18:40.821
You might know that that's
sort of a dubious enterprise

00:18:40.821 --> 00:18:41.800
to a lot of people.

00:18:41.800 --> 00:18:44.587
And some of the stuff I'm doing
in my East Asia casinos people

00:18:44.587 --> 00:18:46.170
are looking at as
maybe being a little

00:18:46.170 --> 00:18:47.631
in the gray area of legality.

00:18:47.631 --> 00:18:49.130
I prefer to have a
government that's

00:18:49.130 --> 00:18:50.730
not going to look
very hard at that.

00:18:50.730 --> 00:18:52.746
That's why I give $200 million.

00:18:52.746 --> 00:18:53.820
I'm worth $30 billion.

00:18:53.820 --> 00:18:55.730
I want to be worth $60 billion.

00:18:55.730 --> 00:18:58.090
I don't want to be worth
$10 billion or in jail.

00:18:58.090 --> 00:18:59.210
And so he laid it out.

00:18:59.210 --> 00:19:01.050
It's all about investment.

00:19:01.050 --> 00:19:03.995
And when the Citizens United
decision unleashed the money

00:19:03.995 --> 00:19:05.620
from the Shelly
Adelson's of the world,

00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:08.903
it had no effect on
the 99.99% of Americans

00:19:08.903 --> 00:19:11.486
who were in no position to give
more than $100,000 or $200,000

00:19:11.486 --> 00:19:12.830
a year in elections.

00:19:12.830 --> 00:19:15.770
It was all about Shelly Adelson
and a few thousand other people

00:19:15.770 --> 00:19:17.810
who can drop $200 million.

00:19:17.810 --> 00:19:20.114
It was their liberation
pact was for them

00:19:20.114 --> 00:19:21.280
to be able to buy elections.

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:22.530
That's what that decision did.

00:19:22.530 --> 00:19:26.020
It had no effect on
99.9% of Americans, zero.

00:19:26.020 --> 00:19:28.044
But for Shelly, it was great.

00:19:28.044 --> 00:19:29.460
Now, let's think
about that money.

00:19:29.460 --> 00:19:34.040
So we outspend most countries
by a great deal of money.

00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:35.590
Germany, as you
might know, recently

00:19:35.590 --> 00:19:37.552
had a national election.

00:19:37.552 --> 00:19:40.010
Just a month ago, they reelected
their Christian democratic

00:19:40.010 --> 00:19:41.291
government.

00:19:41.291 --> 00:19:42.790
And John Nichols
and I went through.

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:43.410
And we did the math.

00:19:43.410 --> 00:19:44.490
We figured out how
much did Germany

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:45.640
spend on their campaigns.

00:19:45.640 --> 00:19:47.890
All their politicians, all
their candidates per voter,

00:19:47.890 --> 00:19:49.740
how much did they spend on
the German national election

00:19:49.740 --> 00:19:50.610
this year?

00:19:50.610 --> 00:19:53.660
And how did that compare to
how much American politicians,

00:19:53.660 --> 00:19:57.670
parties, and third-party groups
spent on our election in 2012?

00:19:57.670 --> 00:20:00.500
For every dollar they
spent in Germany this year,

00:20:00.500 --> 00:20:03.360
for every dollar on campaigns
for their national elections,

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:05.880
we spent $32 on our
national elections,

00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:09.430
congressional and presidential
in 2012-- 32 to 1 ratio.

00:20:09.430 --> 00:20:11.130
And from our research,
basically, that's

00:20:11.130 --> 00:20:13.213
pretty much the ratio
everywhere around the world.

00:20:13.213 --> 00:20:15.410
It's sometimes down
to 8 or 9 or 10 to 1.

00:20:15.410 --> 00:20:17.540
But the larger the country
is, the more it gets up.

00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:20.010
Britain was 29 to 1
for the 2010 election

00:20:20.010 --> 00:20:21.610
compared to us in 2012.

00:20:21.610 --> 00:20:23.590
We spend unbelievable
amounts of money

00:20:23.590 --> 00:20:25.254
compared to these
other countries.

00:20:25.254 --> 00:20:26.670
Now, according to
Citizens United,

00:20:26.670 --> 00:20:28.730
that should give us the
best elections in the world.

00:20:28.730 --> 00:20:29.610
We're outspending them.

00:20:29.610 --> 00:20:30.350
All that speech.

00:20:30.350 --> 00:20:32.220
All that public involvement.

00:20:32.220 --> 00:20:34.220
Well, let's think about that.

00:20:34.220 --> 00:20:36.880
Imagine we outspent
Germany 32 to 1

00:20:36.880 --> 00:20:39.480
in elementary school
education in America.

00:20:39.480 --> 00:20:40.660
What would it be like?

00:20:40.660 --> 00:20:43.550
Take what Germany spends to
educate a first grader and say,

00:20:43.550 --> 00:20:45.884
we outspent them by 32 times.

00:20:45.884 --> 00:20:47.550
What would an American
elementary school

00:20:47.550 --> 00:20:49.930
look like in Oakland today?

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:51.440
You'd have one teacher.

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:53.470
You'd have four students.

00:20:53.470 --> 00:20:55.690
You'd have four
assistant teachers.

00:20:55.690 --> 00:20:58.540
You'd have a music teacher,
an art teacher, a gym teacher,

00:20:58.540 --> 00:21:01.000
a personal trainer, a masseuse.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.370
You'd have this unbelievable
network of people

00:21:03.370 --> 00:21:04.330
to educate our kids.

00:21:04.330 --> 00:21:06.610
Every kid in America
would get an education

00:21:06.610 --> 00:21:08.770
equal to Bill Gates'
kid, if not better.

00:21:08.770 --> 00:21:11.690
32 to 1 spending
advantage over Germany.

00:21:11.690 --> 00:21:12.950
It would be unbelievable.

00:21:12.950 --> 00:21:15.230
So what happens when you
outspend a country 32 to 1

00:21:15.230 --> 00:21:15.890
on elections?

00:21:15.890 --> 00:21:16.690
Unbelievable?

00:21:16.690 --> 00:21:19.380
Yeah, unbelievable but
in the other direction.

00:21:19.380 --> 00:21:21.580
We have the worst
elections in the world.

00:21:21.580 --> 00:21:24.950
Jimmy Carter has said,
again-- and the Carter Center

00:21:24.950 --> 00:21:26.110
monitors elections.

00:21:26.110 --> 00:21:28.410
They've monitored 92
elections in the last 25 years

00:21:28.410 --> 00:21:30.070
to make sure they're
on the up and up.

00:21:30.070 --> 00:21:32.770
Jimmy Carter said
that the United States

00:21:32.770 --> 00:21:35.550
has arguably the worst
election system in the world.

00:21:35.550 --> 00:21:37.320
He said that if the
Carter Center was

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:39.250
asked to monitor an
American election,

00:21:39.250 --> 00:21:41.291
they would refuse to do
so, because we don't meet

00:21:41.291 --> 00:21:43.610
the baseline credibility
level you have to have

00:21:43.610 --> 00:21:46.520
that Venezuela meets,
that Ukraine meets,

00:21:46.520 --> 00:21:47.500
the Belarus meets.

00:21:47.500 --> 00:21:49.159
We don't meet that
baseline criteria

00:21:49.159 --> 00:21:51.200
that they would hold a
country to that they could

00:21:51.200 --> 00:21:53.230
trust the outcome
of the election.

00:21:53.230 --> 00:21:54.550
That's what Carter said.

00:21:54.550 --> 00:21:58.000
Our elections are deplorable
by international standards.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.100
We get the lowest
turnout rate in the world

00:22:00.100 --> 00:22:01.130
among major countries.

00:22:01.130 --> 00:22:03.220
Germany had a 72% turnout.

00:22:03.220 --> 00:22:06.440
Norway, three weeks before
their national election, 82%.

00:22:06.440 --> 00:22:10.520
We had just under 53% of
18-year-olds and older vote

00:22:10.520 --> 00:22:11.580
in our 2012 election.

00:22:11.580 --> 00:22:12.560
People were ecstatic.

00:22:12.560 --> 00:22:14.020
53%.

00:22:14.020 --> 00:22:14.840
Unbelievable.

00:22:14.840 --> 00:22:16.760
We're very low.

00:22:16.760 --> 00:22:18.100
And where does the money go?

00:22:18.100 --> 00:22:20.360
And this is really why
so much has been spent.

00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:22.490
The money goes
overwhelmingly to television

00:22:22.490 --> 00:22:24.050
political advertising.

00:22:24.050 --> 00:22:25.960
And this is much of
what our book is about,

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:30.820
because it's become the lingua
franca of American politics.

00:22:30.820 --> 00:22:34.250
In 1776, the book that
drove most Americans

00:22:34.250 --> 00:22:36.560
to be willing to fight to
make this country independent

00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:39.060
was a pamphlet by Tom Paine
called "Common Sense."

00:22:39.060 --> 00:22:41.460
And it was the most widely
read book of its period,

00:22:41.460 --> 00:22:43.540
perhaps even more
so than the Bible.

00:22:43.540 --> 00:22:45.610
And in the first sentence
of that book, it says,

00:22:45.610 --> 00:22:47.690
a long habit of not
thinking something

00:22:47.690 --> 00:22:51.291
wrong gives it the superficial
appearance of being right.

00:22:51.291 --> 00:22:53.540
And that's how most of us
are about American politics.

00:22:53.540 --> 00:22:55.960
We're so inundated in the
idea of political advertising

00:22:55.960 --> 00:22:58.810
as the lingua franca, we think
that's what democracy is.

00:22:58.810 --> 00:23:01.090
That's what we think
democratic elections are.

00:23:01.090 --> 00:23:01.930
Wrong.

00:23:01.930 --> 00:23:03.680
It's not like that at all.

00:23:03.680 --> 00:23:05.000
Not like that at all.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:06.450
Political advertising
is outlawed

00:23:06.450 --> 00:23:08.236
in all the countries
I just named.

00:23:08.236 --> 00:23:09.360
You can't do it in Germany.

00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:10.443
You can't do it in Norway.

00:23:10.443 --> 00:23:12.110
They don't allow it to be spent.

00:23:12.110 --> 00:23:14.690
That's where we spent $6 of
our $10 billion last time

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:16.320
on these political
ads, which are

00:23:16.320 --> 00:23:18.462
of extraordinarily
dubious value.

00:23:18.462 --> 00:23:20.170
In other countries,
like Britain, they're

00:23:20.170 --> 00:23:23.250
considered to political
campaigns what germ warfare is

00:23:23.250 --> 00:23:25.000
considered to
conventional warfare.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.120
They're considered simply
outside the boundaries

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:29.490
of a healthy democracy
and unacceptable.

00:23:29.490 --> 00:23:31.560
But in this country,
that's what we have.

00:23:31.560 --> 00:23:33.690
And in this country,
increasingly what we have

00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:34.880
are negative ads.

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:36.930
Ads that, basically,
are all about attacking

00:23:36.930 --> 00:23:38.990
the opponent in a
scurrilous manner

00:23:38.990 --> 00:23:43.130
with a factual basis that is
laughable at the most part.

00:23:43.130 --> 00:23:44.260
I could go on and on.

00:23:44.260 --> 00:23:46.730
I think you get the hint
of where we're going.

00:23:46.730 --> 00:23:50.620
The good news though, we are
on a chance of changing it.

00:23:50.620 --> 00:23:54.120
The bad news though is that the
one institution that normally

00:23:54.120 --> 00:23:56.662
would be at the front of leading
us would be our news media,

00:23:56.662 --> 00:23:58.870
our political journalism,
which would draw people in,

00:23:58.870 --> 00:23:59.934
make them aware.

00:23:59.934 --> 00:24:01.600
And the crisis we
talk about in the book

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:03.117
is not only of our
election system,

00:24:03.117 --> 00:24:04.700
but it's of the
collapse of journalism

00:24:04.700 --> 00:24:07.033
as we know it in the United
States in the last 20 years.

00:24:07.033 --> 00:24:10.330
The resources going to
journalism have plummeted.

00:24:10.330 --> 00:24:12.460
In most communities we go
to, there are maybe 30%,

00:24:12.460 --> 00:24:14.990
35% the number of paid
reporters there were,

00:24:14.990 --> 00:24:18.650
including digital,
from 1990 or 1992.

00:24:18.650 --> 00:24:20.560
In some communities,
it's much less.

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:22.190
There's just not
much journalism left.

00:24:22.190 --> 00:24:23.790
The commercial
community has decided

00:24:23.790 --> 00:24:24.760
you can't make money doing it.

00:24:24.760 --> 00:24:25.800
They're not doing it.

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:28.760
Most people who go to vote
now, they have no information

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:30.959
whatsoever about most of
the races on the ballot.

00:24:30.959 --> 00:24:33.250
What little journalism you
get for the races at the top

00:24:33.250 --> 00:24:35.990
is usually just regurgitating
the claims in the TV ads

00:24:35.990 --> 00:24:37.600
and discussing them
and how effective

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:41.100
they are, very little about the
actual candidates or policies.

00:24:41.100 --> 00:24:43.140
So very much the
crisis of dollarocracy

00:24:43.140 --> 00:24:46.420
is the crisis of the loss
and collapse of journalism.

00:24:46.420 --> 00:24:49.110
And the solution to
the crisis is not only

00:24:49.110 --> 00:24:52.890
changing our election laws,
changing our Constitution

00:24:52.890 --> 00:24:56.130
to guarantee the right to
vote, but also creating

00:24:56.130 --> 00:24:58.365
a healthy, vibrant,
independent news media.

00:24:58.365 --> 00:24:59.990
And on that note,
I'd like to introduce

00:24:59.990 --> 00:25:01.878
my co-author, John Nichols.

00:25:01.878 --> 00:25:09.348
