00:27:09.710 --> 00:27:14.630
as the input of information
as regard to democracy.

00:27:14.630 --> 00:27:17.660
They're not even getting
sufficient information

00:27:17.660 --> 00:27:21.210
to get them to know what
to Google to find out

00:27:21.210 --> 00:27:23.440
more about their democracy.

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:25.180
When they watch
their local evening

00:27:25.180 --> 00:27:28.790
news, what they get in
most of this country

00:27:28.790 --> 00:27:34.500
is weather, a lot of weather.

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:36.570
In fact, the fact
of the matter is

00:27:36.570 --> 00:27:38.030
I don't even
understand how you can

00:27:38.030 --> 00:27:40.970
have weather reports
in California.

00:27:40.970 --> 00:27:43.307
But I have watched it here.

00:27:43.307 --> 00:27:44.390
No, I come from Wisconsin.

00:27:44.390 --> 00:27:45.360
We have weather.

00:27:45.360 --> 00:27:49.060
It's going to snow tonight.

00:27:49.060 --> 00:27:51.760
But if you watch the
local evening news,

00:27:51.760 --> 00:27:54.730
it begins with-- I don't
care what's going on.

00:27:54.730 --> 00:27:58.660
The government is shut
down, debt ceiling crisis,

00:27:58.660 --> 00:28:01.040
death, grief, hate,
sorrow, whatever.

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:02.550
They'll tell you something big.

00:28:02.550 --> 00:28:03.730
And then they'll
say, but first, we're

00:28:03.730 --> 00:28:05.560
going to let you know
about the weather.

00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:09.610
And they will go to a very
handsome or attractive person

00:28:09.610 --> 00:28:12.670
who will sit there
and say, well,

00:28:12.670 --> 00:28:14.530
today we had a lot of weather.

00:28:14.530 --> 00:28:17.169
And I'll be back to tell you
more about it after the break.

00:28:17.169 --> 00:28:19.710
And then they go, and they give
a huge amount of commercials.

00:28:19.710 --> 00:28:24.190
And then they do the
smash and grab news

00:28:24.190 --> 00:28:28.160
of the day-- death, death,
grief, sorrow, robbery,

00:28:28.160 --> 00:28:30.860
car crash, traffic jam, death,
death, grief, sorrow, robbery,

00:28:30.860 --> 00:28:34.150
car crash, traffic jam.

00:28:34.150 --> 00:28:37.124
Most newscasts have about
27 stories mentioned.

00:28:37.124 --> 00:28:39.290
When we ask people, they
often say, oh, a newscaster

00:28:39.290 --> 00:28:40.840
will probably do
three or four stories.

00:28:40.840 --> 00:28:41.340
No.

00:28:41.340 --> 00:28:43.070
They do about 27 hits.

00:28:43.070 --> 00:28:45.900
But it's all just reading
one line after another.

00:28:45.900 --> 00:28:47.690
And it's invariably
something horrible

00:28:47.690 --> 00:28:50.860
going on someplace that makes
you really dislike and distrust

00:28:50.860 --> 00:28:51.990
your neighbors.

00:28:51.990 --> 00:28:54.900
And so once they've got done
with that though jamming that

00:28:54.900 --> 00:28:57.870
in, not enough time to cover
the school board or the city

00:28:57.870 --> 00:29:00.870
council or the state
legislature, mind you.

00:29:00.870 --> 00:29:03.380
Then they get back
to the weather.

00:29:03.380 --> 00:29:04.820
And that's where they let loose.

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:07.194
That's where you're going to
get your detailed and useful

00:29:07.194 --> 00:29:07.860
information.

00:29:07.860 --> 00:29:09.850
They're going to tell
you that in Mountain View

00:29:09.850 --> 00:29:12.570
it was 73 degrees today.

00:29:12.570 --> 00:29:15.970
But up in South San
Francisco, it was 70.

00:29:15.970 --> 00:29:20.394
And over in Palo Alto, it was
71, if you can believe it.

00:29:20.394 --> 00:29:22.560
And then they're going to
go all through the region.

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:24.056
You know this,
because one time you

00:29:24.056 --> 00:29:25.430
watched the locally
evening news.

00:29:25.430 --> 00:29:28.920
And so they go all around
with all that stuff.

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:31.330
And then they give you
the barometric pressure,

00:29:31.330 --> 00:29:33.470
which I've covered journalism.

00:29:33.470 --> 00:29:35.186
I've been a journalist
for 30 years.

00:29:35.186 --> 00:29:37.060
I've watched the evening
news in every place,

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:37.720
not just in this country.

00:29:37.720 --> 00:29:39.511
I've been in 25 countries
around the world.

00:29:39.511 --> 00:29:41.950
I have no idea what
barometric pressure is.

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:43.650
But I understand it's important.

00:29:43.650 --> 00:29:46.630
And they tell you all
about it every night.

00:29:46.630 --> 00:29:48.900
And then what do they do?

00:29:48.900 --> 00:29:50.640
This is the important part.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:52.490
In the seven to
eight minutes devoted

00:29:52.490 --> 00:29:57.950
to weather, they go, well,
over here across the Pacific,

00:29:57.950 --> 00:30:01.240
around Thailand, there seems
to be a storm stirring up.

00:30:01.240 --> 00:30:03.410
And if the wind
blows the right way,

00:30:03.410 --> 00:30:07.520
it might come up across the
Pacific and, I don't want,

00:30:07.520 --> 00:30:11.004
in a couple weeks, we
might have some rain,

00:30:11.004 --> 00:30:11.920
because they did this.

00:30:11.920 --> 00:30:12.800
They look across the whole.

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:14.550
They tell you a weather
patterns as stuff.

00:30:14.550 --> 00:30:17.040
And you're like, wow, this must
be the most important stuff

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:18.380
in my life.

00:30:18.380 --> 00:30:20.260
This must be what
really matters.

00:30:20.260 --> 00:30:24.250
As a citizen, I have to know
this in order to function.

00:30:24.250 --> 00:30:26.454
And then they throw in a
bunch more commercials.

00:30:26.454 --> 00:30:28.120
And then after the
bunch of commercials,

00:30:28.120 --> 00:30:29.744
because you're there
with baited breath

00:30:29.744 --> 00:30:32.180
to know what the weather
will be tomorrow,

00:30:32.180 --> 00:30:33.750
they go around the
whole map again.

00:30:33.750 --> 00:30:35.250
And they say, in
Palo Alto tomorrow,

00:30:35.250 --> 00:30:40.620
it's very likely to be 73 and
up in South San Francisco, 71.

00:30:40.620 --> 00:30:42.290
But take a look at this.

00:30:42.290 --> 00:30:45.360
Mountain View is looking like
it might get to 75 tomorrow.

00:30:45.360 --> 00:30:46.360
We're not sure.

00:30:46.360 --> 00:30:48.600
But we'll be keeping
an eye on that.

00:30:48.600 --> 00:30:51.840
And so they've done seven, eight
minutes of this, seven, eight

00:30:51.840 --> 00:30:55.600
minutes of the central place
where the average American gets

00:30:55.600 --> 00:30:59.800
their information about politics
and governance on the weather.

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:01.340
There's only one problem.

00:31:01.340 --> 00:31:04.490
The weather is free.

00:31:04.490 --> 00:31:06.570
The weather doesn't
require any journalism.

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:09.190
The weather is created
by the government.

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:09.710
I know.

00:31:09.710 --> 00:31:11.740
You're like, hold it.

00:31:11.740 --> 00:31:14.120
They invited another
nut into Google.

00:31:14.120 --> 00:31:14.620
No.

00:31:14.620 --> 00:31:17.950
The weather comes from the
National Weather Service.

00:31:17.950 --> 00:31:19.940
You, the taxpayers,
pay for the collection

00:31:19.940 --> 00:31:21.250
of all that information.

00:31:21.250 --> 00:31:23.350
And the TV stations
get it for free.

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:24.850
They don't pay for it.

00:31:24.850 --> 00:31:29.290
And so they give you seven or
eight minutes of no journalism.

00:31:29.290 --> 00:31:32.419
They don't even go out
and check the thermometer.

00:31:32.419 --> 00:31:33.960
And then at the end
of that newscast,

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:36.240
they say, well, you know
everything you need to know.

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:39.040
Go out there and decide who
should be the President, who

00:31:39.040 --> 00:31:40.650
should be your
senator, how we should

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:43.000
run our local governments,
how you should feel

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:45.350
about major issues
in this country.

00:31:45.350 --> 00:31:48.840
We have a journalism
stand-down in America.

00:31:48.840 --> 00:31:49.610
It is a crisis.

00:31:49.610 --> 00:31:51.622
Local TV is the main source.

00:31:51.622 --> 00:31:52.580
But look at newspapers.

00:31:52.580 --> 00:31:55.100
Newspapers in this
country have laid off

00:31:55.100 --> 00:31:58.830
22,000 employees since 2009.

00:31:58.830 --> 00:32:00.560
And every one of
them blames Google.

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:04.470
So just be aware that they all
are like, it's the internet.

00:32:04.470 --> 00:32:06.110
But you know what
the problem was?

00:32:06.110 --> 00:32:08.100
I've got good news for Google.

00:32:08.100 --> 00:32:09.980
They were laying
them off before.

00:32:09.980 --> 00:32:11.480
The fact of the
matter is the crisis

00:32:11.480 --> 00:32:15.710
in newspaper journalism
started in 1950.

00:32:15.710 --> 00:32:19.280
And we have had a steady decline
in the number of newspapers

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:21.540
in this country since the '50s.

00:32:21.540 --> 00:32:24.180
And it was television much
more than the internet

00:32:24.180 --> 00:32:25.530
that caused this crisis.

00:32:25.530 --> 00:32:28.230
What the internet did
was take the ads away.

00:32:28.230 --> 00:32:30.620
And this is a big deal,
because journalism

00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:33.940
in America for a long
time was sustained by ads.

00:32:33.940 --> 00:32:37.850
And everybody thought,
wow, what wonderful people.

00:32:37.850 --> 00:32:41.080
All those big companies, the
car companies and the soda

00:32:41.080 --> 00:32:43.870
companies, they just
give all this money

00:32:43.870 --> 00:32:48.570
to newspapers and television
and radio to sustain journalism.

00:32:48.570 --> 00:32:51.286
Well, it turns out, ironically
enough, they didn't.

00:32:51.286 --> 00:32:53.310
They gave that
money because that

00:32:53.310 --> 00:32:56.350
was the vehicle by which
they could get to you.

00:32:56.350 --> 00:32:57.610
And so you got a newspaper.

00:32:57.610 --> 00:32:58.550
You looked at it.

00:32:58.550 --> 00:33:02.470
You didn't want to look at
the ad for the diapers but OK.

00:33:02.470 --> 00:33:05.030
Sp then the next thing--
that's how they sold stuff.

00:33:05.030 --> 00:33:06.580
TV the same way.

00:33:06.580 --> 00:33:08.500
It doesn't happen
that way anymore.

00:33:08.500 --> 00:33:10.540
That's not how it works.

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:14.290
I get my little phone here,
even when I'm on Twitter.

00:33:14.290 --> 00:33:16.360
I was tweeting about
this incredible event.

00:33:16.360 --> 00:33:19.410
And I've got little ads
coming on Twitter now.

00:33:19.410 --> 00:33:21.390
The ads find me.

00:33:21.390 --> 00:33:22.270
You know this.

00:33:22.270 --> 00:33:23.520
I don't have to tell you this.

00:33:23.520 --> 00:33:25.450
The ads follow people around.

00:33:25.450 --> 00:33:28.510
The bottom line is
the ads don't go.

00:33:28.510 --> 00:33:31.620
The ads don't go in
the newspaper anymore.

00:33:31.620 --> 00:33:35.020
They don't go, by and
large, on TV anymore.

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:38.040
And so you have this deep
decline in journalism.

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:39.960
There is one set of
ads that do come in.

00:33:39.960 --> 00:33:41.632
One set of ads do come in.

00:33:41.632 --> 00:33:42.840
And that's the political ads.

00:33:42.840 --> 00:33:45.190
And you know why?

00:33:45.190 --> 00:33:46.492
You're just a screwed up bunch.

00:33:46.492 --> 00:33:48.200
We've got a couple of
white-haired folks.

00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:48.970
And I love you.

00:33:48.970 --> 00:33:51.230
But by and large, you're
too young to vote.

00:33:51.230 --> 00:33:57.690
In this country, the voting
class is old people, quite old.

00:33:57.690 --> 00:34:00.120
That's why we can't
talk about anything

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:01.860
but social security
in this country,

00:34:01.860 --> 00:34:04.170
because the fact of the
matter is our voting class

00:34:04.170 --> 00:34:05.395
is overwhelmingly old.

00:34:05.395 --> 00:34:07.520
And people think just about
presidential elections.

00:34:07.520 --> 00:34:08.020
No.

00:34:08.020 --> 00:34:11.210
You've got to go down that
food chain into local politics.

00:34:11.210 --> 00:34:13.550
Bob talked about a 52% turnout.

00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:16.860
Well, 52%, 53% of our
voting age population,

00:34:16.860 --> 00:34:19.310
that's the mountaintop.

00:34:19.310 --> 00:34:21.219
You go into state
and local elections,

00:34:21.219 --> 00:34:24.520
you start creeping down to
numbers that are in, literally,

00:34:24.520 --> 00:34:28.320
20%, 18%, 17%, 16%,
15%, 10% turnouts.

00:34:28.320 --> 00:34:30.440
We just elected Cory
Booker to the US Senate

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:33.570
from New Jersey in a
20% turnout election.

00:34:33.570 --> 00:34:35.670
That means if you met
five people on the street,

00:34:35.670 --> 00:34:37.010
four of them didn't vote.

00:34:37.010 --> 00:34:39.192
Well, roughly half of them
voted for Cory Booker.

00:34:39.192 --> 00:34:41.650
That means he's going to the
United States Senate, the most

00:34:41.650 --> 00:34:43.870
elite club in the
world with the support

00:34:43.870 --> 00:34:47.969
of 10% of the electorate in the
state he's going to represent.

00:34:47.969 --> 00:34:49.929
So we've got this
huge stand-down.

00:34:49.929 --> 00:34:52.610
By and large, the people
who do vote are much older.

00:34:52.610 --> 00:34:55.420
They still watch that
television evening news.

00:34:55.420 --> 00:34:57.130
And so what do they get?

00:34:57.130 --> 00:34:58.990
All the weather
they can possibly

00:34:58.990 --> 00:35:04.660
use and then $6
billion worth of ads.

00:35:04.660 --> 00:35:07.740
I don't think I have to explain
to people as smart as you

00:35:07.740 --> 00:35:11.290
that what that leaves us with
is in the ideal propaganda

00:35:11.290 --> 00:35:13.060
circumstance, right?

00:35:13.060 --> 00:35:15.330
No information.

00:35:15.330 --> 00:35:16.830
No information for
the voting class

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:18.700
that's of any
particular consequence

00:35:18.700 --> 00:35:21.780
but a massive inflow of ads.

00:35:21.780 --> 00:35:23.020
And what do those ads do?

00:35:23.020 --> 00:35:25.860
What do they tell people to do?

00:35:25.860 --> 00:35:26.860
Don't vote.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:32.540
Imagine that
political ads are put

00:35:32.540 --> 00:35:35.100
on TV to get people to vote.

00:35:35.100 --> 00:35:37.830
That's not the point,
because remember,

00:35:37.830 --> 00:35:39.970
we have a small voting class.

00:35:39.970 --> 00:35:41.990
We have depressed our
voting class down.

00:35:41.990 --> 00:35:45.630
And as we talk about in
the book, in many races,

00:35:45.630 --> 00:35:49.140
as much as 90% to 95%
of the ads are negative.

00:35:49.140 --> 00:35:50.560
And ask yourself this.

00:35:50.560 --> 00:35:52.860
I'm going to take
this guy right here.

00:35:52.860 --> 00:35:56.620
I'm going to say, you're
a sophisticated urban

00:35:56.620 --> 00:35:58.580
intellectual, right?

00:35:58.580 --> 00:36:01.584
You vote on a variety of
issues that concern you deeply.

00:36:01.584 --> 00:36:03.250
I'm going to make
assumptions about you.

00:36:03.250 --> 00:36:05.100
And I probably am wrong.

00:36:05.100 --> 00:36:07.790
But I'm going to assume you
believe that people have

00:36:07.790 --> 00:36:09.530
the right to make
choices at what

00:36:09.530 --> 00:36:10.920
they do with their own body.

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:15.900
You believe that social
engineering by the right wing,

00:36:15.900 --> 00:36:17.330
I don't want that.

00:36:17.330 --> 00:36:19.499
I'm not going to vote
for some right wing

00:36:19.499 --> 00:36:21.540
Rick Santorum for President
of the United States.

00:36:21.540 --> 00:36:23.415
That's just not where
I'm going, because I've

00:36:23.415 --> 00:36:24.460
got the cool glasses.

00:36:24.460 --> 00:36:26.340
That's not who I'm going to be.

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:27.070
All right.

00:36:27.070 --> 00:36:27.570
Cool.

00:36:27.570 --> 00:36:29.800
So you see a negative
ad about the candidate

00:36:29.800 --> 00:36:31.610
you decided to vote for.

00:36:31.610 --> 00:36:34.120
You're going to vote for
this progressive candidate.

00:36:34.120 --> 00:36:36.490
They're thinking liberally
on a whole bunch of things.

00:36:36.490 --> 00:36:38.370
You see a negative ad
about that candidate.

00:36:38.370 --> 00:36:40.280
And you're like,
well, that's it.

00:36:40.280 --> 00:36:42.630
I'm voting for the
social conservative.

00:36:42.630 --> 00:36:44.660
I'm going to vote
against everything

00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:47.650
I believe in, because I saw a
negative ad about my candidate.

00:36:47.650 --> 00:36:49.349
That's not what happens.

00:36:49.349 --> 00:36:51.390
You see enough negative
ads about that candidate,

00:36:51.390 --> 00:36:53.920
you say, a pox on
all their houses.

00:36:53.920 --> 00:36:55.360
I'm just not going to vote.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:57.810
And you stand down.

00:36:57.810 --> 00:37:00.390
We talk a lot in this country
about voter suppression,

00:37:00.390 --> 00:37:03.360
about voter ID laws,
and about other efforts

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:04.730
to make it hard to vote.

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:07.810
The number one voter
suppression in America

00:37:07.810 --> 00:37:11.140
is negative ads, because
negative ads tell

00:37:11.140 --> 00:37:14.460
tens of millions of Americans in
the primary place where they're

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:17.895
getting information about
politics still, don't vote.

00:37:17.895 --> 00:37:20.270
Don't vote for the candidate
that you wanted to vote for,

00:37:20.270 --> 00:37:21.686
because it turns
out that they are

00:37:21.686 --> 00:37:25.440
the most evil
person in the world.

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:27.260
We actually did
this for the book.

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:29.950
We watched these ads.

00:37:29.950 --> 00:37:31.030
California, right?

00:37:31.030 --> 00:37:33.700
They don't campaign
in California anymore,

00:37:33.700 --> 00:37:36.290
because you guys have
figured things out.

00:37:36.290 --> 00:37:38.780
So bottom line is they go
to the handful of states

00:37:38.780 --> 00:37:40.800
where they're like this
incredible creature,

00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:43.090
the undecided voter.

00:37:43.090 --> 00:37:45.210
Many of them live in the
Midwest where I'm from.

00:37:45.210 --> 00:37:47.168
There are the kind of
people that can't decide.

00:37:47.168 --> 00:37:47.950
I don't know.

00:37:47.950 --> 00:37:49.320
Should I get up this morning?

00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:53.420
And so the end result
is they pour these ads

00:37:53.420 --> 00:37:54.290
into these states.

00:37:54.290 --> 00:37:56.500
They are really awful.

00:37:56.500 --> 00:38:00.290
They are unbelievably
troubling things.

00:38:00.290 --> 00:38:01.130
Slasher films.

00:38:01.130 --> 00:38:02.790
Nothing compared to this stuff.

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:04.910
And so people are
inundated with this.

00:38:04.910 --> 00:38:07.610
And it tells them to
stand down from politics.

00:38:07.610 --> 00:38:08.780
It's a really serious issue.

00:38:08.780 --> 00:38:11.470
And this issue gets more
serious by the minute,

00:38:11.470 --> 00:38:16.870
because in this country, we
have a bigger and bigger divide

00:38:16.870 --> 00:38:19.940
between the handful of
engaged people, the people who

00:38:19.940 --> 00:38:21.549
do-- they're like
Eric over here.

00:38:21.549 --> 00:38:22.590
They're looking stuff up.

00:38:22.590 --> 00:38:25.720
He's probably looking up the
turnout numbers right now.

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:28.490
And so we have a handful
of hyper-engaged people.

00:38:28.490 --> 00:38:33.040
But then we have a growing
disconnect in this country.

00:38:33.040 --> 00:38:37.020
And it's why it is
possible for people

00:38:37.020 --> 00:38:38.830
to shut down the government.

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:40.750
It is why it is
possible for us to have

00:38:40.750 --> 00:38:44.520
huge crises in Washington
about things that--

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:47.410
and you're a relatively
young guy here.

00:38:47.410 --> 00:38:49.660
I know this is
going to shock you.

00:38:49.660 --> 00:38:52.560
Old people like me,
when I was growing up,

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:55.780
I never knew there was such
a thing as a continuing

00:38:55.780 --> 00:38:57.210
resolution.

00:38:57.210 --> 00:39:00.570
I never knew there was such
a thing as a debt ceiling.

00:39:00.570 --> 00:39:02.540
I didn't know about
government shutdown.

00:39:02.540 --> 00:39:05.010
I've covered politics forever.

00:39:05.010 --> 00:39:06.480
I didn't know that.

00:39:06.480 --> 00:39:07.870
That never happened.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:10.180
Now, it's all we talk about.

00:39:10.180 --> 00:39:12.090
Why is it all we talk about?

00:39:12.090 --> 00:39:14.150
Because when we
have depressed down

00:39:14.150 --> 00:39:16.050
our political
participation, when

00:39:16.050 --> 00:39:19.190
we have squeezed
information out of the game,

00:39:19.190 --> 00:39:22.300
we create a game for
a handful of people,

00:39:22.300 --> 00:39:25.290
a tiny number of
people, who participate

00:39:25.290 --> 00:39:27.300
in gerrymandered
political circumstances.

00:39:27.300 --> 00:39:29.520
Remember, now, in
America, it's the opposite

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:31.360
of what we think about.

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:33.180
Generally, voters
choose the candidates.

00:39:33.180 --> 00:39:35.220
In America, the candidates,
the politicians,

00:39:35.220 --> 00:39:36.540
choose their districts.

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:38.290
They choose their set of voters.

00:39:38.290 --> 00:39:41.294
So if you're a certain
Democrat, here's

00:39:41.294 --> 00:39:42.710
how we're going
to draw the lines.

00:39:42.710 --> 00:39:43.980
The legislature
of California has

00:39:43.980 --> 00:39:45.146
tried to break some of that.

00:39:45.146 --> 00:39:47.240
But most of the country,
that's what they do.

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:51.500
So the end result is
across this country

00:39:51.500 --> 00:39:53.650
when you have a
Congress-- and remember,

00:39:53.650 --> 00:39:55.520
this Congress didn't
win, by the way.

00:39:55.520 --> 00:39:57.228
This is an important
thing to understand.

00:39:57.228 --> 00:39:59.600
Last year, 1.7
million more people

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:02.350
voted for Democrats for the
House of Representatives

00:40:02.350 --> 00:40:03.684
than voted for Republicans.

00:40:03.684 --> 00:40:05.100
But because of the
gerrymandering,

00:40:05.100 --> 00:40:08.630
because of structural flaws
in how we do our elections,

00:40:08.630 --> 00:40:10.380
the Republicans have
control of the House,

00:40:10.380 --> 00:40:13.320
not because more people
wanted them to, but because

00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:16.040
of the structures of
how we do our politics.

00:40:16.040 --> 00:40:19.520
The end result is that those
people who are there, everybody

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:21.972
said, well, why don't the
Republicans stand down?

00:40:21.972 --> 00:40:22.930
Why don't they realize?

00:40:22.930 --> 00:40:24.620
This is incredibly unpopular.

00:40:24.620 --> 00:40:27.680
The Gallup Poll just showed
that the Republican Party

00:40:27.680 --> 00:40:30.150
has a lower approval
rating today

00:40:30.150 --> 00:40:32.530
that at any time since
Gallup started polling

00:40:32.530 --> 00:40:34.190
on the approval
of major parties.

00:40:34.190 --> 00:40:36.950
It's unbelievable.

00:40:36.950 --> 00:40:40.650
Ted Cruz is still saying,
I didn't do anything wrong.

00:40:40.650 --> 00:40:42.490
And why?

00:40:42.490 --> 00:40:46.620
Because they don't fear
November elections.

00:40:46.620 --> 00:40:49.020
They don't fear
the mass turnout.

00:40:49.020 --> 00:40:50.187
They've drawn the districts.

00:40:50.187 --> 00:40:51.394
They've structured the money.

00:40:51.394 --> 00:40:52.730
They've structured the politics.

00:40:52.730 --> 00:40:55.650
So the only problem they've
got is their primary.

00:40:55.650 --> 00:40:57.520
They don't want to be
challenged by somebody

00:40:57.520 --> 00:41:00.920
who is more extreme
than they are.

00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:03.480
And so as a result, you
end up with a situation

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:07.380
where your entire politics,
the governance of the nation,

00:41:07.380 --> 00:41:11.340
is defined by people
who are afraid of people

00:41:11.340 --> 00:41:13.710
who are crazier than they are.

00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:16.650
That, I want to tell you,
is not a healthy democracy.

00:41:16.650 --> 00:41:19.060
Amazingly enough, this is not
what Jefferson and Madison

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:21.980
imagined back in 1787.

00:41:21.980 --> 00:41:24.050
And so as we approach
all these issues,

00:41:24.050 --> 00:41:27.860
we realize we're not at
the full crisis point yet.

00:41:27.860 --> 00:41:32.970
We are moving rapidly toward
it, because this next election

00:41:32.970 --> 00:41:34.440
cycle, we had $10 billion.

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:37.020
And by the way, here's a little
something for Google to do.

00:41:37.020 --> 00:41:39.690
When we started the research
on this-- one of you

00:41:39.690 --> 00:41:43.070
could do this, because I
have such reverence for you.

00:41:43.070 --> 00:41:44.250
One of you could do this.

00:41:44.250 --> 00:41:46.900
Do know that there's no
agency in America that

00:41:46.900 --> 00:41:49.100
charts all the
money that's spent?

00:41:49.100 --> 00:41:49.810
It's independent.

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:51.950
The Federal Election Commission
doesn't begin to do it.

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:54.366
Independent groupings do it
at the federal or state level.

00:41:54.366 --> 00:41:56.490
Nobody does it nationwide
what all is spent.

00:41:56.490 --> 00:41:57.860
We did it for our book.

00:41:57.860 --> 00:41:58.840
It was incredibly hard.

00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:00.000
It took the better
part of the year.

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.240
We went state by state,
community by community.

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:04.870
What we saw was huge amounts of
money flooded into local races,

00:42:04.870 --> 00:42:07.390
where you get the most power,
where you decide on zoning,

00:42:07.390 --> 00:42:10.250
where you decide on delivery of
services and things like that.

00:42:10.250 --> 00:42:12.980
A San Jose race where they
spent half million dollars

00:42:12.980 --> 00:42:14.820
for a city council seat.

00:42:14.820 --> 00:42:16.400
California referendums.

00:42:16.400 --> 00:42:18.750
Last year in
California, $550 million

00:42:18.750 --> 00:42:22.722
was spent on referendums in
California, these initiatives,

00:42:22.722 --> 00:42:24.180
particularly that
tell you that you

00:42:24.180 --> 00:42:27.190
don't want to know whether your
food is genetically modified.

00:42:27.190 --> 00:42:29.950
And so the end result
of this is that we

00:42:29.950 --> 00:42:33.670
come into this situation in a
very troubling point, the point

00:42:33.670 --> 00:42:36.620
where it could get a lot worse.

00:42:36.620 --> 00:42:42.060
And what we propose is to think
like you folks think I hope.

00:42:42.060 --> 00:42:44.360
I hope I'm not making too
much of an assumption.

00:42:44.360 --> 00:42:46.460
And that is you don't
look at a problem

00:42:46.460 --> 00:42:48.840
from the standpoint of
what everybody's done up

00:42:48.840 --> 00:42:50.700
to this point to
solve the problem.

00:42:50.700 --> 00:42:52.620
You don't narrow your options.

00:42:52.620 --> 00:42:55.080
You say, how do
we fix the crisis?

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:59.660
What we need to do in America
is do massive interventions

00:42:59.660 --> 00:43:00.990
in how we communicate.

00:43:00.990 --> 00:43:03.850
We have to figure out
how to democratize

00:43:03.850 --> 00:43:06.680
the flow of information,
so that working

00:43:06.680 --> 00:43:10.420
class people, the mom who
works at a Wendy's window

00:43:10.420 --> 00:43:12.560
and then has to go
home and put three kids

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:14.550
to sleep and then has
to go out that night

00:43:14.550 --> 00:43:16.190
and work at the
McDonald's window,

00:43:16.190 --> 00:43:18.770
how she gets enough
information to be

00:43:18.770 --> 00:43:21.610
a participant in
our democratic life,

00:43:21.610 --> 00:43:23.650
how it is not cut
off from her and all

00:43:23.650 --> 00:43:25.170
she sees is negative ads.

00:43:25.170 --> 00:43:27.022
So we have to think
a lot about that.

00:43:27.022 --> 00:43:28.730
But we also have to
think a lot about how

00:43:28.730 --> 00:43:30.590
to renew our democracy.

00:43:30.590 --> 00:43:33.500
And this is big deal stuff.

00:43:33.500 --> 00:43:35.300
We have to amend
our constitution.

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:36.850
There's nothing wrong with that.

00:43:36.850 --> 00:43:38.380
I know when somebody says,
amend the Constitution, you say,

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:39.160
that's impossible.

00:43:39.160 --> 00:43:40.560
It's never been done.

00:43:40.560 --> 00:43:43.150
The Constitution was written
in stone, handed down

00:43:43.150 --> 00:43:44.980
on tablets to Michele Bachmann.

00:43:44.980 --> 00:43:50.580
And it's never been altered,
well, except for 27 times.

00:43:50.580 --> 00:43:53.360
27 times we've amended
our Constitution.

00:43:53.360 --> 00:43:55.680
The founders amended it
10 times in the first four

00:43:55.680 --> 00:43:57.470
years of the Republic.

00:43:57.470 --> 00:44:00.470
And then about a decade later,
when the vice president shot

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:02.110
the secretary of
the treasury, they

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:04.000
decided to amend
it again to pick

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.100
a different way of
getting vice presidents.

00:44:06.100 --> 00:44:08.050
And so we've amended
the Constitution

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:10.960
throughout our
history as a country.

00:44:10.960 --> 00:44:15.540
We have amended it most often
to make our democracy work.

00:44:15.540 --> 00:44:16.770
Everybody loves the New Deal.

00:44:16.770 --> 00:44:18.110
We talk about Roosevelt.

00:44:18.110 --> 00:44:20.600
One of the lost realities
of the New Deal era

00:44:20.600 --> 00:44:22.142
was at the start of
the New Deal era,

00:44:22.142 --> 00:44:23.933
they did two amendments
to the Constitution

00:44:23.933 --> 00:44:25.260
that no one ever talks about.

00:44:25.260 --> 00:44:26.480
Eric can look them up.

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:30.280
And the one amendment said that
when a president is elected,

00:44:30.280 --> 00:44:32.800
instead of being sworn
in in the spring,

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:34.310
he's sworn in in January.

00:44:34.310 --> 00:44:35.534
That moved the process down.

00:44:35.534 --> 00:44:37.950
Remember we talked, some of
the older folks will remember,

00:44:37.950 --> 00:44:40.810
the story of Roosevelt's
first 100 days.

00:44:40.810 --> 00:44:44.050
We made possible the
meaning of a first 100 days

00:44:44.050 --> 00:44:46.192
by collapsing in the
time between the election

00:44:46.192 --> 00:44:47.400
and when he became president.

00:44:47.400 --> 00:44:48.160
That was huge.

00:44:48.160 --> 00:44:50.743
The other thing we did was say
that the Congress of the United

00:44:50.743 --> 00:44:54.450
States met immediately
in January, rather than

00:44:54.450 --> 00:44:55.769
deep into the next year.

00:44:55.769 --> 00:44:57.810
Previously, before that,
the way the Constitution

00:44:57.810 --> 00:44:59.660
was structured,
Congress was elected.

00:44:59.660 --> 00:45:01.270
The people who were
elected did not

00:45:01.270 --> 00:45:03.900
come in to sit until
well into the next year.

00:45:03.900 --> 00:45:06.680
As a result, those who
had been defeated actually

00:45:06.680 --> 00:45:09.920
governed for the better part
of a year after the election.

00:45:09.920 --> 00:45:12.310
We changed these things to
make our democracy work.

00:45:12.310 --> 00:45:14.280
And we did a lot
of other changes.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:15.999
We gave women the right to vote.

00:45:15.999 --> 00:45:18.040
After the Civil War, we
gave African American men

00:45:18.040 --> 00:45:19.510
the right to vote.

00:45:19.510 --> 00:45:21.680
We gave Native Americans
the right to vote.

00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:24.540
In 1962, in the lifetime of
some people in this room,

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:26.534
we struck down the
wealth barrier to voting

00:45:26.534 --> 00:45:27.200
in this country.

00:45:27.200 --> 00:45:32.320
We banned the poll tax
constitutionally in 1962.

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:36.350
1970 we said that people
who are 18 to 21 years old,

00:45:36.350 --> 00:45:38.120
who go off and fight
in wars, get drafted

00:45:38.120 --> 00:45:39.620
to die in foreign
lands, ought to be

00:45:39.620 --> 00:45:42.740
able to vote in the elections
that would determine

00:45:42.740 --> 00:45:44.320
whether we fight those wars.

00:45:44.320 --> 00:45:47.420
We have amended our Constitution
again and again and again

00:45:47.420 --> 00:45:51.370
in this country to repair the
problems of our democracy.

00:45:51.370 --> 00:45:54.900
And the great gap today is that
because our media is so bad,

00:45:54.900 --> 00:45:57.050
because it doesn't
cover politics,

00:45:57.050 --> 00:45:59.010
our media covers Washington.

00:45:59.010 --> 00:46:01.200
It covers dysfunction
in Washington.

00:46:01.200 --> 00:46:02.930
Most people don't
know that we are

00:46:02.930 --> 00:46:04.930
in another
constitutional moment.

00:46:04.930 --> 00:46:08.830
16 American states have
formally petitioned the Congress

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:12.700
of the United States to overturn
the Citizens United ruling

00:46:12.700 --> 00:46:15.470
and to say corporations
are not people.

00:46:15.470 --> 00:46:16.674
Money is not speech.

00:46:16.674 --> 00:46:18.340
And we the citizens
of the United States

00:46:18.340 --> 00:46:21.430
have a right to form elections
in which the vote matters more

00:46:21.430 --> 00:46:22.230
than the dollar.

00:46:22.230 --> 00:46:24.530
16 American states
have already done this.

00:46:24.530 --> 00:46:28.829
500 communities across the
country have done this.

00:46:28.829 --> 00:46:30.370
Los Angeles did it
earlier this year.

00:46:30.370 --> 00:46:31.540
San Francisco has
already done it.

00:46:31.540 --> 00:46:33.720
I wouldn't be surprised if
Mountain View has done it.

00:46:33.720 --> 00:46:35.261
But the fact of the
matter is there's

00:46:35.261 --> 00:46:39.060
this huge cry across this
country to make the change.

00:46:39.060 --> 00:46:41.070
And the interesting
thing is it's not just

00:46:41.070 --> 00:46:42.690
Democrats and liberals.

00:46:42.690 --> 00:46:44.852
The fact of the matter
is everybody gets this.

00:46:44.852 --> 00:46:46.810
Last year, they put a
referendums on the ballot

00:46:46.810 --> 00:46:49.100
in Montana and in Colorado.

00:46:49.100 --> 00:46:50.760
Colorado was an Obama state.

00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:52.370
Montana was a Romney state.

00:46:52.370 --> 00:46:55.140
They had a referendum on a
Constitutional amendment.

00:46:55.140 --> 00:46:59.610
Each state voted roughly
73% in favor of doing it.

00:46:59.610 --> 00:47:01.320
Republican members
of legislatures

00:47:01.320 --> 00:47:03.320
across this country have
worked with Democrats

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:04.340
to encourage this.

00:47:04.340 --> 00:47:05.840
Recently we got the
first Republican

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:09.190
in Congress, Walter Jones, a
deep passionate conservative

00:47:09.190 --> 00:47:11.100
from the Carolinas,
to sign on and say,

00:47:11.100 --> 00:47:12.910
we need this
constitutional amendment.

00:47:12.910 --> 00:47:16.540
Because if we don't
make democracy changes

00:47:16.540 --> 00:47:19.840
to our Constitution, as hard
as it is with all the barriers

00:47:19.840 --> 00:47:23.510
that are out there, we cannot
begin to structure the money

00:47:23.510 --> 00:47:26.427
out, and to structure
the people in.

00:47:26.427 --> 00:47:27.510
So that's the bottom line.

00:47:27.510 --> 00:47:30.841
I come and ask you think
of yourselves as founders.

00:47:30.841 --> 00:47:32.215
Think of yourselves
as people who

00:47:32.215 --> 00:47:34.870
want to shape an actual
democracy in this country.

00:47:34.870 --> 00:47:37.200
And then because of
your special genius,

00:47:37.200 --> 00:47:38.830
think of yourselves
as people who

00:47:38.830 --> 00:47:41.530
