But explore these ideas,
because we genuinely

00:53:34.460 --> 00:53:37.320
need a lot of smart people
in the mix of figuring out

00:53:37.320 --> 00:53:39.890
how we create a communication
system that sustains democracy.

00:53:39.890 --> 00:53:41.610
AUDIENCE: So many
fascinating issues.

00:53:41.610 --> 00:53:44.050
We could talk for hours
about all of them, I'm sure.

00:53:44.050 --> 00:53:45.716
The one I wanted to
ask you about though

00:53:45.716 --> 00:53:48.620
was the 28th Amendment
that you're proposing.

00:53:48.620 --> 00:53:51.650
I totally share your values
and objectives there.

00:53:51.650 --> 00:53:54.820
Yet I do remain a little bit
skeptical about the limitation

00:53:54.820 --> 00:53:56.450
on using money.

00:53:56.450 --> 00:53:59.530
This is the way that people
speak in this country

00:53:59.530 --> 00:54:00.200
oftentimes.

00:54:00.200 --> 00:54:04.090
And there were
issues where I agree

00:54:04.090 --> 00:54:05.840
with the funding, a
billionaire coming in,

00:54:05.840 --> 00:54:08.100
whether it's Larry or
Sergei funding something

00:54:08.100 --> 00:54:09.300
on a carbon tax.

00:54:09.300 --> 00:54:12.660
So I'm wondering why
not have a thing where

00:54:12.660 --> 00:54:14.850
you do the first part
of it, where you say,

00:54:14.850 --> 00:54:18.950
only entities that can vote in
this election can contribute.

00:54:18.950 --> 00:54:21.790
Any person who can vote
can contribute unlimitedly

00:54:21.790 --> 00:54:22.457
with disclosure.

00:54:22.457 --> 00:54:24.040
And I know the Supreme
Court is trying

00:54:24.040 --> 00:54:26.530
to fight some of the
disclosure parts of this.

00:54:26.530 --> 00:54:28.400
What would be the
problem with that?

00:54:28.400 --> 00:54:31.140
It seems to me that that
preserves free speech, as well

00:54:31.140 --> 00:54:34.340
as freedom of association,
that I think are very vital.

00:54:34.340 --> 00:54:38.900
And footnote, our values
are winning actually.

00:54:38.900 --> 00:54:41.390
If you read things
like "Victory Lab,"

00:54:41.390 --> 00:54:42.640
we can spend the money better.

00:54:42.640 --> 00:54:45.310
So why would we want
from a utilitarian point

00:54:45.310 --> 00:54:46.477
of view unilaterally disarm?

00:54:46.477 --> 00:54:48.434
JOHN NICHOLS: Let me take
a quick piece of that

00:54:48.434 --> 00:54:49.610
and let Bob take it.

00:54:49.610 --> 00:54:51.630
Eric, I love you.

00:54:51.630 --> 00:54:52.301
You're the man.

00:54:52.301 --> 00:54:54.050
You were looking up
the Powell memo there.

00:54:54.050 --> 00:54:54.790
Come on.

00:54:54.790 --> 00:54:58.410
And you're doing exactly
what we want you to do.

00:54:58.410 --> 00:55:01.641
When we come out, we don't
specify a specific amendment.

00:55:01.641 --> 00:55:03.766
We actually think there
are several amendments that

00:55:03.766 --> 00:55:04.500
ought to be done.

00:55:04.500 --> 00:55:06.410
We think a Supreme
Court that tells you

00:55:06.410 --> 00:55:08.760
that money should flow
easily into politics,

00:55:08.760 --> 00:55:11.970
but it should be hard to vote
is wrong on several counts.

00:55:11.970 --> 00:55:13.980
So we would like to not
only do an amendment

00:55:13.980 --> 00:55:15.170
as regards to the
money, we would also

00:55:15.170 --> 00:55:16.190
like to do an
amendment that says,

00:55:16.190 --> 00:55:17.898
everybody has a right
to vote and a right

00:55:17.898 --> 00:55:19.290
to have that vote counted.

00:55:19.290 --> 00:55:21.830
But what you've just done
is exactly what we want.

00:55:21.830 --> 00:55:25.480
You are talking about how you
would sculpt that amendment.

00:55:25.480 --> 00:55:27.730
And the fact of the
matter is every amendment

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:30.330
to the Constitution of
any consequence has not

00:55:30.330 --> 00:55:33.540
come about wholly
formed at the beginning.

00:55:33.540 --> 00:55:37.136
It ends up with people starting
to think about the idea,

00:55:37.136 --> 00:55:38.760
thinking about what
they want to render

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:41.400
and what they want to defend,
and making something real.

00:55:41.400 --> 00:55:43.750
And so I don't disregard
a lot of what you say.

00:55:43.750 --> 00:55:46.870
Although Bob may toss
you off completely.

00:55:46.870 --> 00:55:49.970
But what I will tell you
is that kind of engagement

00:55:49.970 --> 00:55:51.010
is where we have to be.

00:55:51.010 --> 00:55:53.980
Our problem in America is we're
not having those discussions.

00:55:53.980 --> 00:55:56.350
We're not talking about
how to structurally make

00:55:56.350 --> 00:55:57.260
this thing work.

00:55:57.260 --> 00:55:58.210
And a final thing
I'll tell you about

00:55:58.210 --> 00:55:59.293
constitutional amendments.

00:55:59.293 --> 00:56:00.750
This is a big deal.

00:56:00.750 --> 00:56:03.050
When you talk about a
constitutional amendment,

00:56:03.050 --> 00:56:05.950
you don't always have to
get it to fix the problem.

00:56:05.950 --> 00:56:07.630
This is the interesting thing.

00:56:07.630 --> 00:56:10.342
When we had the Equal
Rights Amendment,

00:56:10.342 --> 00:56:11.800
the women in the
room will be aware

00:56:11.800 --> 00:56:13.960
that it's not been enacted.

00:56:13.960 --> 00:56:16.940
We don't have an Equal Rights
Amendment to our Constitution.

00:56:16.940 --> 00:56:19.870
But the multi-year fight to
get an Equal Rights Amendment

00:56:19.870 --> 00:56:22.270
helped to open the
door for Title IX,

00:56:22.270 --> 00:56:26.380
for workplace protections for
women, for Lilly Ledbetter Act,

00:56:26.380 --> 00:56:28.560
and a host of other
breakthroughs.

00:56:28.560 --> 00:56:31.050
On the right and the left,
a constitutional amendment

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:34.630
strategy does not have
to be completed in order

00:56:34.630 --> 00:56:37.460
to begin to address the
crisis along the way.

00:56:37.460 --> 00:56:40.519
But if you don't shoot big,
if you don't go for something

00:56:40.519 --> 00:56:42.060
to say, this is such
a serious issue,

00:56:42.060 --> 00:56:43.470
we have to talk
about it in this way,

00:56:43.470 --> 00:56:45.511
you don't possibly get to
the incremental changes

00:56:45.511 --> 00:56:46.344
along the way.

00:56:46.344 --> 00:56:47.760
ROBERT W. MCCHESNEY:
Well, I think

00:56:47.760 --> 00:56:49.969
the problem with
unlimited spending

00:56:49.969 --> 00:56:51.260
is what I talked about already.

00:56:51.260 --> 00:56:51.930
I won't repeat it.

00:56:51.930 --> 00:56:53.340
There's a difference
between a small spending

00:56:53.340 --> 00:56:54.560
and a large spending.

00:56:54.560 --> 00:56:57.960
And the other problem is that
it also reinforces the idea

00:56:57.960 --> 00:56:59.600
that politics is
for billionaires

00:56:59.600 --> 00:57:00.970
and really wealthy people.

00:57:00.970 --> 00:57:02.477
And we get to be spectators.

00:57:02.477 --> 00:57:04.560
If you have money, you can
buy in and be a player.

00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:06.760
If you don't, you just
hope that your team wins.

00:57:06.760 --> 00:57:09.052
You root for the billionaire
you most agree with.

00:57:09.052 --> 00:57:10.760
And I don't think
that's a healthy thing.

00:57:10.760 --> 00:57:13.030
I think that we look at
how other democracies that

00:57:13.030 --> 00:57:16.790
are much more successful by
all the criteria, whoever

00:57:16.790 --> 00:57:19.950
makes them, wealthy people have
a lot of influence in society.

00:57:19.950 --> 00:57:23.190
They don't need
to buy elections.

00:57:23.190 --> 00:57:24.220
They can start groups.

00:57:24.220 --> 00:57:25.780
They can do education campaigns.

00:57:25.780 --> 00:57:27.850
There's lots of ways they
can influence politics

00:57:27.850 --> 00:57:29.060
if that's their goal.

00:57:29.060 --> 00:57:31.634
The election process should
be kept, as much as possible,

00:57:31.634 --> 00:57:32.550
a level playing field.

00:57:32.550 --> 00:57:35.100
That really is
mandatory for democracy

00:57:35.100 --> 00:57:36.240
to be credible and succeed.

00:57:36.240 --> 00:57:38.232
And that's what we've
lost in this country.

00:57:38.232 --> 00:57:40.440
Now, your other point though
I completely agree with.

00:57:40.440 --> 00:57:42.984
The premise of our book
is that this is not

00:57:42.984 --> 00:57:43.900
a reactionary country.

00:57:43.900 --> 00:57:45.320
This is not a dumb country.

00:57:45.320 --> 00:57:47.352
This is not a
country that buys in.

00:57:47.352 --> 00:57:49.560
The great tension here is
when we go around to talks,

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:52.730
this is the smallest room
we've played in 40 talks.

00:57:52.730 --> 00:57:53.550
People get it.

00:57:53.550 --> 00:57:54.300
They're concerned.

00:57:54.300 --> 00:57:56.350
This is a progressive country.

00:57:56.350 --> 00:57:58.470
Young people, in
particular, are really

00:57:58.470 --> 00:58:01.060
queued in that we've got to
change this governing system.

00:58:01.060 --> 00:58:02.430
It's not working.

00:58:02.430 --> 00:58:04.730
And that's why
we're so optimistic.

00:58:04.730 --> 00:58:06.250
And I think the
key point I would

00:58:06.250 --> 00:58:08.690
close with as we're getting
near the witching hour

00:58:08.690 --> 00:58:12.460
is that it's striking that
in the last five years

00:58:12.460 --> 00:58:15.630
this great movement has been
on two fronts politically.

00:58:15.630 --> 00:58:17.860
One is to unleash the
power of unlimited money

00:58:17.860 --> 00:58:20.350
by the wealthiest
institutions and individuals.

00:58:20.350 --> 00:58:22.877
On the other hand, the
Supreme Court has worked hard

00:58:22.877 --> 00:58:24.460
and state governments
have worked hard

00:58:24.460 --> 00:58:27.126
to make it harder and harder for
poor people and people of color

00:58:27.126 --> 00:58:30.125
to vote, literally reenacting
Jim Crow statutes now

00:58:30.125 --> 00:58:31.360
in five Southern states.

00:58:31.360 --> 00:58:32.550
Something that is obscene.

00:58:32.550 --> 00:58:34.930
It would've been
illegal two years ago.

00:58:34.930 --> 00:58:37.490
The reason why they're doing
that, making it easy for money

00:58:37.490 --> 00:58:39.380
to flood elections, making
it harder for poor people

00:58:39.380 --> 00:58:40.840
to get to the
polls, is they know

00:58:40.840 --> 00:58:42.240
they can't win a fair election.

00:58:42.240 --> 00:58:45.600
That system is
really that fragile.

00:58:45.600 --> 00:58:46.764
We just need to organize.

00:58:46.764 --> 00:58:47.430
And we will win.

00:58:47.430 --> 00:58:49.570
We need to recognize that we
have the numbers on our side.

00:58:49.570 --> 00:58:51.030
We have the wind at our sails.

00:58:51.030 --> 00:58:52.360
They're a dying system.

00:58:52.360 --> 00:58:54.696
That's what they're doing
this monkey in Congress, where

00:58:54.696 --> 00:58:56.320
they're trying to
stall the government.

00:58:56.320 --> 00:58:58.510
Any of the issues they're
trying to push through

00:58:58.510 --> 00:59:00.170
would never pass a fair test.

00:59:00.170 --> 00:59:01.810
So they've got to close the
government down, put a gun

00:59:01.810 --> 00:59:04.040
at the head, and say, you
give us our way or we shoot,

00:59:04.040 --> 00:59:05.310
because the know if they
have to put it to a vote,

00:59:05.310 --> 00:59:06.110
they would lose.

00:59:06.110 --> 00:59:08.115
They can only do
it by blackmail.

00:59:08.115 --> 00:59:12.150
AUDIENCE: So given the amount
of money that goes into

00:59:12.150 --> 00:59:18.030
or the fact that news
sources are so often funded

00:59:18.030 --> 00:59:20.613
by large groups, large
individuals, people

00:59:20.613 --> 00:59:22.983
with a lot of money
and whatnot, do

00:59:22.983 --> 00:59:25.780
you have any recommendations
for either news sources or ways

00:59:25.780 --> 00:59:28.480
to determine that the news
sources you're listening to

00:59:28.480 --> 00:59:30.030
aren't simply
giving you the news

00:59:30.030 --> 00:59:33.930
that someone with a lot of power
and/or money wants you to know?

00:59:33.930 --> 00:59:36.360
JOHN NICHOLS: Well, let me
begin by saying, of course,

00:59:36.360 --> 00:59:41.040
you could just Google a
good news source, right?

00:59:41.040 --> 00:59:41.900
I'm teasing.

00:59:41.900 --> 00:59:45.139
AUDIENCE: So the
problem is, sure, you

00:59:45.139 --> 00:59:46.055
can find news sources.

00:59:46.055 --> 00:59:46.979
But you don't know--

00:59:46.979 --> 00:59:48.520
JOHN NICHOLS: That's
what I'm saying.

00:59:48.520 --> 00:59:50.212
But that's what
people actually do.

00:59:50.212 --> 00:59:52.170
Poor people across America,
they're like, well,

00:59:52.170 --> 00:59:53.340
I've got to find something.

00:59:53.340 --> 00:59:55.760
And unfortunately
what they end up with

00:59:55.760 --> 00:59:57.600
isn't always as
genius as Google is.

00:59:57.600 --> 00:59:59.850
They don't always end up
with the perfect news source.

00:59:59.850 --> 01:00:02.760
And so the answer
to the question

01:00:02.760 --> 01:00:06.590
is diversity and
encountering voices.

01:00:06.590 --> 01:00:08.600
We get this question
everywhere we go.

01:00:08.600 --> 01:00:10.520
And the first thing I
always tell people is,

01:00:10.520 --> 01:00:13.170
read something that you
really disagree with a lot.

01:00:13.170 --> 01:00:13.670
I'm serious.

01:00:16.250 --> 01:00:17.950
I write for "The
Nation" magazine.

01:00:17.950 --> 01:00:20.199
Our equivalent is arguably
"National Review,"

01:00:20.199 --> 01:00:21.490
the very conservative magazine.

01:00:21.490 --> 01:00:23.820
I read "National
Review" all the time.

01:00:23.820 --> 01:00:25.100
It's pretty well written.

01:00:25.100 --> 01:00:28.570
I think they've become a little
bit more scared of their base.

01:00:28.570 --> 01:00:31.260
But the bottom line is I still
read them on a regular basis.

01:00:31.260 --> 01:00:32.090
And I find it very important.

01:00:32.090 --> 01:00:33.840
I read a lot of
conservative publications,

01:00:33.840 --> 01:00:36.050
because I think that
helps to inform me.

01:00:36.050 --> 01:00:37.876
I also read international
publications,

01:00:37.876 --> 01:00:40.250
because I want to read about
America from the perspective

01:00:40.250 --> 01:00:41.470
that other people see it.

01:00:41.470 --> 01:00:43.644
So I go to "The Guardian"
a lot in Britain.

01:00:43.644 --> 01:00:45.060
I think they're
very, very useful.

01:00:45.060 --> 01:00:47.100
I go to a lot of the
German publications, which

01:00:47.100 --> 01:00:50.950
have great English language
translation, because I'm not

01:00:50.950 --> 01:00:52.330
the best German speaker.

01:00:52.330 --> 01:00:55.355
And the bottom line
is that when you

01:00:55.355 --> 01:00:57.230
start to read about how
other people see you,

01:00:57.230 --> 01:00:59.021
it starts to give you
a lot of perspective.

01:00:59.021 --> 01:01:02.600
I happen to like "Deutsche
Welle." "Der Spiegel's," I

01:01:02.600 --> 01:01:05.020
think, coverage of the US
is actually quite good.

01:01:05.020 --> 01:01:06.590
And so go for all that.

01:01:06.590 --> 01:01:09.244
But this is the conundrum.

01:01:09.244 --> 01:01:10.660
So I hope that
helps a little bit.

01:01:10.660 --> 01:01:12.576
But the question you ask
gets to the conundrum

01:01:12.576 --> 01:01:14.710
of what we're talking
about, because all

01:01:14.710 --> 01:01:16.760
across America-- I don't
care who we're with.

01:01:16.760 --> 01:01:19.410
I don't care if we're in a
church basement or union hall

01:01:19.410 --> 01:01:21.890
or in Google or
wherever we're at,

01:01:21.890 --> 01:01:24.890
people say, how do I figure
out what I can trust?

01:01:24.890 --> 01:01:26.780
Well, the answer
to that question

01:01:26.780 --> 01:01:29.650
is, you can't trust anybody.

01:01:29.650 --> 01:01:31.760
What you can trust
is a diverse system

01:01:31.760 --> 01:01:33.755
that gives you a lot of
different perspectives.

01:01:33.755 --> 01:01:35.130
And then you search
through that.

01:01:35.130 --> 01:01:37.410
You find things
that, ultimately,

01:01:37.410 --> 01:01:39.430
touch you that mean
something to you.

01:01:39.430 --> 01:01:41.590
And then you use all of that.

01:01:41.590 --> 01:01:44.370
But increasingly in
America, people are getting

01:01:44.370 --> 01:01:48.130
a one-size-fits-all bit of
news that is more likely to be

01:01:48.130 --> 01:01:52.205
defined by a negative campaign
ad than by a detailed smart bit

01:01:52.205 --> 01:01:53.122
of coverage.

01:01:53.122 --> 01:01:54.830
ROBERT W. MCCHESNEY:
Just to add to that.

01:01:54.830 --> 01:01:59.450
The sort of partisanization
this of news in America,

01:01:59.450 --> 01:02:01.090
especially cable
news, is directly

01:02:01.090 --> 01:02:03.180
a function of the
lack of journalism,

01:02:03.180 --> 01:02:07.060
because this is actually Rupert
Murdoch's brilliant business

01:02:07.060 --> 01:02:08.770
move what he did with Fox News.

01:02:08.770 --> 01:02:10.660
It wasn't that he said,
let's have a channel

01:02:10.660 --> 01:02:12.576
that will simply
give the Republican

01:02:12.576 --> 01:02:13.950
Party talking
points every night.

01:02:13.950 --> 01:02:15.160
So if you want to know
what they're thinking,

01:02:15.160 --> 01:02:16.370
you can go to this channel.

01:02:16.370 --> 01:02:18.661
Instead, he said, if I don't
have any journalists, if I

01:02:18.661 --> 01:02:21.590
don't cover anything, if I
don't have a news room, what can

01:02:21.590 --> 01:02:23.300
I do to make people
come to my channel?

01:02:23.300 --> 01:02:25.300
Well, you give them opinions.

01:02:25.300 --> 01:02:26.880
You give them ideologies.

01:02:26.880 --> 01:02:29.480
So he hired
charismatic presenters

01:02:29.480 --> 01:02:31.280
to present the talking points.

01:02:31.280 --> 01:02:33.230
And it's very inexpensive to do.

01:02:33.230 --> 01:02:34.710
John does cable
news all the time.

01:02:34.710 --> 01:02:37.760
There are no reporters or
people covering anything there.

01:02:37.760 --> 01:02:39.140
You've got producers
and bookers.

01:02:39.140 --> 01:02:40.160
But they don't do
any journalism.

01:02:40.160 --> 01:02:41.660
They just give
you talking points

01:02:41.660 --> 01:02:43.890
on the issues of the day.

01:02:43.890 --> 01:02:46.030
And this reinforces
the sense that people

01:02:46.030 --> 01:02:47.990
are going into their
self-defined little cubby

01:02:47.990 --> 01:02:48.180
holes.

01:02:48.180 --> 01:02:50.055
They're not seeing what
the rest of the world

01:02:50.055 --> 01:02:52.070
sees, because I would
read "National Review."

01:02:52.070 --> 01:02:54.280
I subscribe to "The Economist"
and "Financial Times."

01:02:54.280 --> 01:02:56.190
They are core reading for me.

01:02:56.190 --> 01:02:57.732
But I go to Fox News.

01:02:57.732 --> 01:02:59.190
And after three
minutes, I'm bored.

01:02:59.190 --> 01:03:00.981
I know the Republican
Party talking points.

01:03:00.981 --> 01:03:03.529
They aren't educating me
on any interesting ideas.

01:03:03.529 --> 01:03:05.820
And I suspect a conservative
would go to MSNBC and feel

01:03:05.820 --> 01:03:08.585
the same way, not
to pick on MSNBC.

01:03:08.585 --> 01:03:10.710
JOHN NICHOLS: When you and
I'm on, it's quite good.

01:03:10.710 --> 01:03:12.100
ROBERT W. MCCHESNEY: When
John's on, it's different.

01:03:12.100 --> 01:03:13.929
But if we had
substantive reporting,

01:03:13.929 --> 01:03:16.345
I think that issue about people
being in their cubby holes

01:03:16.345 --> 01:03:18.006
would disappear,
because I remember

01:03:18.006 --> 01:03:19.880
this wasn't an issue 30
or 40 years ago, when

01:03:19.880 --> 01:03:21.720
we had much more
substantial reporting

01:03:21.720 --> 01:03:22.970
across the political spectrum.

01:03:22.970 --> 01:03:24.660
And it was routine
that people on the left

01:03:24.660 --> 01:03:26.576
would read conservative
and conservative left.

01:03:26.576 --> 01:03:27.730
It wasn't considered weird.

01:03:27.730 --> 01:03:28.970
Today, it's sort of
weird if you watch

01:03:28.970 --> 01:03:30.810
Fox News for any length of
time for any of my friends,

01:03:30.810 --> 01:03:32.630
you think, what are
you badgering yourself

01:03:32.630 --> 01:03:34.654
with this idiocy
for, to be blunt.

01:03:34.654 --> 01:03:36.070
JOHN NICHOLS: To
popcorn off this,

01:03:36.070 --> 01:03:37.010
I'll give you one final point.

01:03:37.010 --> 01:03:38.520
I was once traveling
from Jerusalem

01:03:38.520 --> 01:03:40.717
to Bethlehem on a
Palestinian bus.

01:03:40.717 --> 01:03:42.300
This kid is sitting
next to me, and he

01:03:42.300 --> 01:03:46.710
had three newspapers
on his lap--

01:03:46.710 --> 01:03:50.570
or six newspapers-- three Hebrew
language papers, three Arabic

01:03:50.570 --> 01:03:51.840
language papers.

01:03:51.840 --> 01:03:53.490
And he's 15, 16 years old.

01:03:53.490 --> 01:03:56.110
I said, what's up
with that, man?

01:03:56.110 --> 01:03:57.047
Are you a paper boy?

01:03:57.047 --> 01:03:57.880
And he said, no, no.

01:03:57.880 --> 01:03:59.256
I try to read them
all every day,

01:03:59.256 --> 01:04:01.338
because I'm trying to
figure out this whole thing.

01:04:01.338 --> 01:04:03.050
I mean we've got this
thing with the Jews

01:04:03.050 --> 01:04:05.130
and the Palestinians
and the Christians.

01:04:05.130 --> 01:04:07.780
And I want to get it right.

01:04:07.780 --> 01:04:10.210
Well, I love that kid, right?

01:04:10.210 --> 01:04:11.954
That's what we're
supposed to do.

01:04:11.954 --> 01:04:14.370
And actually, what you folks
do, when you Google something

01:04:14.370 --> 01:04:16.080
and you get a lot
of articles up,

01:04:16.080 --> 01:04:18.999
that's a very good
model of that.

01:04:18.999 --> 01:04:20.540
But the bottom line
is, again, I want

01:04:20.540 --> 01:04:23.115
to emphasize the people who
are doing that, that kid was

01:04:23.115 --> 01:04:26.710
a self-selected-- he's probably
in the Palestinian parliament

01:04:26.710 --> 01:04:31.130
today or whatever or maybe
the Israeli parliament.

01:04:31.130 --> 01:04:35.450
But the bottom line
is that most Americans

01:04:35.450 --> 01:04:37.755
are rushing through their
lives very, very fast.

01:04:37.755 --> 01:04:39.090
It's faster than ever.

01:04:39.090 --> 01:04:41.740
And they're getting little
snippets of information.

01:04:41.740 --> 01:04:43.970
And unfortunately, the
constant information

01:04:43.970 --> 01:04:46.450
they get on politics
repeated again and again

01:04:46.450 --> 01:04:51.450
is the negative ad 100
times, 1,000 times.

01:04:51.450 --> 01:04:53.560
In some media
markets, you can see

01:04:53.560 --> 01:04:57.330
ads for a particular candidate
as much as 2,000 or 3,000 times

01:04:57.330 --> 01:04:58.340
before an election.

01:04:58.340 --> 01:04:59.730
You're going to remember that.

01:04:59.730 --> 01:05:02.990
You're not going to remember
a little quick newscast.

01:05:02.990 --> 01:05:06.301
AUDIENCE: I really enjoyed your
previous book, "Our Media."

01:05:06.301 --> 01:05:07.300
ROBERT W. MCCHESNEY: Oh.

01:05:07.300 --> 01:05:08.215
That's an oldy.

01:05:08.215 --> 01:05:10.500
AUDIENCE: So I have a
question about this claim

01:05:10.500 --> 01:05:15.410
that the political advertising
is reducing participation

01:05:15.410 --> 01:05:18.860
because it also draws out
the fringes, at least that's

01:05:18.860 --> 01:05:20.690
what they say in the media.

01:05:20.690 --> 01:05:25.070
But the question I have
is about the hypothesis

01:05:25.070 --> 01:05:28.890
that really previously
we had either newspapers

01:05:28.890 --> 01:05:30.590
or we had three big networks.

01:05:30.590 --> 01:05:32.180
And everyone got
all of their news

01:05:32.180 --> 01:05:34.790
from the national
and then the local,

01:05:34.790 --> 01:05:37.170
during the '70s
when I was a kid.

01:05:37.170 --> 01:05:40.100
And now, it's fractured into all
of these specialized networks

01:05:40.100 --> 01:05:42.890
that echo your preferences.

01:05:42.890 --> 01:05:46.720
So before people were
educated because they

01:05:46.720 --> 01:05:49.230
had no other outlets
and so they were stuck

01:05:49.230 --> 01:05:53.790
with a more broad presentation
of the issues of the day,

01:05:53.790 --> 01:05:55.750
and now they don't
have that, so there

01:05:55.750 --> 01:05:58.560
are things like "Democracy
Now" that does great reporting

01:05:58.560 --> 01:06:03.520
but has a very small readership,
I guess, or audience.

01:06:03.520 --> 01:06:07.100
So it seems like you have
to get the news, good news,

01:06:07.100 --> 01:06:09.380
adjacent to how people are
living their busy lives.

01:06:09.380 --> 01:06:11.110
So that seems like
a bigger problem,

01:06:11.110 --> 01:06:13.040
even though we should
fix campaign finance.

01:06:13.040 --> 01:06:15.560
JOHN NICHOLS: Believe
me, we wrote this book

01:06:15.560 --> 01:06:16.907
to not make that division.

01:06:16.907 --> 01:06:18.490
To say, we've got
to fix our politics.

01:06:18.490 --> 01:06:20.365
ROBERT W. MCCHESNEY: Media
right in the middle of it.

01:06:20.365 --> 01:06:21.850
JOHN NICHOLS: But
one of the things I

01:06:21.850 --> 01:06:23.145
do, and I didn't do it here
because I didn't get here

01:06:23.145 --> 01:06:23.776
in time.

01:06:23.776 --> 01:06:25.150
I often go when
I come to a town,

01:06:25.150 --> 01:06:28.190
and I go to an antique store.

01:06:28.190 --> 01:06:30.260
They have stacks of the
old papers from the town.

01:06:30.260 --> 01:06:33.521
And I get the local daily
paper from 50 years ago.

01:06:33.521 --> 01:06:35.020
And I just hold it
up to the people.

01:06:35.020 --> 01:06:36.644
And we would go
through the front page.

01:06:36.644 --> 01:06:38.120
We go through a
couple pages of it.

01:06:38.120 --> 01:06:42.200
People's jaws drop, because
local daily newspapers

01:06:42.200 --> 01:06:45.590
50 years ago, the range
of things they covered

01:06:45.590 --> 01:06:47.050
would blow your mind.

01:06:47.050 --> 01:06:49.320
They had three or four
pages of international news.

01:06:49.320 --> 01:06:53.110
Even in the local paper
in Palo Alto or San Jose,

01:06:53.110 --> 01:06:56.290
they had news from states
around the country.

01:06:56.290 --> 01:06:58.540
I was in Duluth,
Minnesota, once.

01:06:58.540 --> 01:06:59.600
And I picked up a paper.

01:06:59.600 --> 01:07:03.400
It had a Ralph Nader press
conference from 50 years

01:07:03.400 --> 01:07:04.760
ago or roughly 50 years ago.

01:07:04.760 --> 01:07:06.200
It had civil rights stuff.

01:07:06.200 --> 01:07:08.140
It had labor stuff,
all this stuff.

01:07:08.140 --> 01:07:11.660
Well, we have squeezed
it down to such an extent

01:07:11.660 --> 01:07:15.010
that it isn't just
that they had three

01:07:15.010 --> 01:07:17.540
networks and their local
paper in those days.

01:07:17.540 --> 01:07:21.230
The institutions actually gave
them a lot of information.

01:07:21.230 --> 01:07:24.210
It was considered the
way that you did it.

01:07:24.210 --> 01:07:26.080
And people also got magazines.

01:07:26.080 --> 01:07:27.080
Do you know what I mean?

01:07:27.080 --> 01:07:28.970
They had many sources.

01:07:28.970 --> 01:07:31.990
Today, we have much more
access to information.

01:07:31.990 --> 01:07:37.630
But in the cacophony, we
don't have that easy access

01:07:37.630 --> 01:07:39.790
where you live and
in your community,

01:07:39.790 --> 01:07:41.589
because that local
paper that I pick up,

01:07:41.589 --> 01:07:43.880
in addition to all that global
stuff and all that stuff

01:07:43.880 --> 01:07:47.560
from around the country,
also had a reporter who

01:07:47.560 --> 01:07:50.610
was tasked every day to
go cover the school board,

01:07:50.610 --> 01:07:54.570
a reporter tasked every day
to go cover the city council.

01:07:54.570 --> 01:07:55.960
When you read
through that paper,

01:07:55.960 --> 01:07:59.070
you knew what was happening
in your community.

01:07:59.070 --> 01:08:02.630
And today, it is
very hard, if you

01:08:02.630 --> 01:08:05.260
live in a suburb
around San Francisco,

01:08:05.260 --> 01:08:07.200
to know what's happening
in your community,

01:08:07.200 --> 01:08:11.110
unless some desperate citizen
blogger is out there doing

01:08:11.110 --> 01:08:11.710
the game.

01:08:11.710 --> 01:08:14.001
But the only problem with
that is the desperate citizen

01:08:14.001 --> 01:08:18.827
blogger might not actually be
trying to give the full story.

01:08:18.827 --> 01:08:20.910
ROBERT W. MCCHESNEY: The
crucial point here again,

01:08:20.910 --> 01:08:23.479
not to be Johnny One
Note, is that we've

01:08:23.479 --> 01:08:24.960
lost resources to journalism.

01:08:24.960 --> 01:08:28.300
And I think that resources to
journalism, people get paid.

01:08:28.300 --> 01:08:29.760
They're responsible for a beat.

01:08:29.760 --> 01:08:31.350
There are competing
journalists covering it.

01:08:31.350 --> 01:08:33.433
So if someone misses it,
someone else will get it.

01:08:33.433 --> 01:08:35.830
So there's that
spur of competition.

01:08:35.830 --> 01:08:37.149
We've lost that.

01:08:37.149 --> 01:08:39.547
And I've made a career of
being critical of the type

01:08:39.547 --> 01:08:41.880
of journalism we came out of,
as you know from our media

01:08:41.880 --> 01:08:43.390
and not theirs.

01:08:43.390 --> 01:08:45.160
And the problem is
that I think we've

01:08:45.160 --> 01:08:47.850
had a tendency to look at
old media versus new media.

01:08:47.850 --> 01:08:51.302
And there's a split there, when
that's an irrelevant concern.

01:08:51.302 --> 01:08:52.760
They are really
these concerns that

01:08:52.760 --> 01:08:55.170
are using different
technologies at this point.

01:08:55.170 --> 01:08:57.890
And the great crisis is
that on the digital realm

01:08:57.890 --> 01:09:00.380
with advertising no longer
supporting journalism,

01:09:00.380 --> 01:09:02.149
there aren't the
resources for journalism.

01:09:02.149 --> 01:09:04.449
And it's worse online
than it is in old media.

01:09:04.449 --> 01:09:05.990
That's the last
place there are still

01:09:05.990 --> 01:09:07.790
funds going to pay journalists.

01:09:07.790 --> 01:09:10.250
If we lose online journalists,
the reporting, like John

01:09:10.250 --> 01:09:12.910
does for "The Nation," he gets
paid from a print publication.

01:09:12.910 --> 01:09:14.240
But he's all over the web.

01:09:14.240 --> 01:09:16.649
I mean every day he's
posting articles to the web.

01:09:16.649 --> 01:09:18.819
If "The Nation" can't
afford to pay him anymore

01:09:18.819 --> 01:09:20.727
because they can't
stay in business,

01:09:20.727 --> 01:09:22.560
then John is not writing
on the web anymore.

01:09:22.560 --> 01:09:25.101
That's the irony of our times
is old media is supporting much

01:09:25.101 --> 01:09:26.950
of the original
content we consider

01:09:26.950 --> 01:09:29.649
what we get we go
online to see news.

01:09:29.649 --> 01:09:31.149
Because you're here
at Google, and I

01:09:31.149 --> 01:09:34.649
know this is a great concern
of yours, that there's content

01:09:34.649 --> 01:09:37.229
online that you can
then deliver to people

01:09:37.229 --> 01:09:39.915
and make it useful to people.

01:09:39.915 --> 01:09:42.733
I think this issue of how we're
going to somehow get resources

01:09:42.733 --> 01:09:44.899
to independent competing
journalists who are getting

01:09:44.899 --> 01:09:49.220
paid to do work and cover
elections and cover communities

01:09:49.220 --> 01:09:50.562
is just foundational.

01:09:50.562 --> 01:09:51.770
Just keep that in your minds.

01:09:51.770 --> 01:09:54.002
It's certainly the
issue we work on.

01:09:54.002 --> 01:09:55.710
JOHN NICHOLS: And one
last element there,

01:09:55.710 --> 01:09:58.360
as long as Eric is here,
because Eric Googles stuff.

